const PART5_MEDIUM2 = [
  {id:"p5m2_1",question:"The committee is said _____ reached a decision, though no announcement has been made.",options:["A) to have","B) to be","C) having","D) to having"],answer:"A",explanation:"'Is said to have reached' is correct because passive reporting verbs (is said/reported/believed + to + perfect infinitive) express a claim about a completed past action without identifying the source, a common structure in formal news writing. 'To be' is wrong because the simple infinitive 'to be reached' would imply a present state, not a completed action. 'Having' is wrong because a bare participle cannot follow a passive reporting verb; an infinitive marker 'to' is required. 'To having' is wrong because 'to' as an infinitive marker must be followed by a base verb, not a gerund.",category:"Grammar"},
  {id:"p5m2_2",question:"The new facility is reported _____ completed ahead of the original schedule.",options:["A) to be","B) to have been","C) having been","D) being"],answer:"B",explanation:"'Is reported to have been completed' is correct because the passive reporting structure requires a perfect passive infinitive ('to have been + past participle') when the reported action was completed before the time of reporting. 'To be' is wrong because 'to be completed' refers to a future or present completion, not one that has already occurred. 'Having been' is wrong because a bare participle phrase cannot directly follow a passive reporting verb; an infinitive 'to' is required. 'Being' is wrong because the present participle 'being' cannot follow a passive reporting verb in standard English grammar.",category:"Grammar"},
  {id:"p5m2_3",question:"It is widely believed _____ the company will announce a merger within weeks.",options:["A) that","B) which","C) what","D) for"],answer:"A",explanation:"'That' is correct because the impersonal passive structure 'It is believed/thought/reported + that-clause' requires the subordinating conjunction 'that' to introduce the content clause, as the subject 'it' is a dummy placeholder. 'Which' is wrong because 'which' is a relative pronoun used to refer to a specific antecedent noun, not to introduce a content clause. 'What' is wrong because 'what' functions as a pronoun meaning 'the thing that,' which creates a grammatically incoherent structure after 'believed.' 'For' is wrong because 'for' is a preposition and cannot introduce a finite that-clause after a passive reporting verb.",category:"Grammar"},
  {id:"p5m2_4",question:"The CEO is thought _____ considering retirement after 15 years at the helm.",options:["A) to be","B) being","C) that he is","D) both A and C"],answer:"A",explanation:"'To be' is correct because the personal passive reporting structure requires a present infinitive: 'The CEO is thought to be considering retirement' follows the pattern 'subject + passive reporting verb + to + infinitive,' which is the only grammatical way to complete this sentence. 'Being' is wrong because a bare present participle cannot directly follow a passive reporting verb; the infinitive marker 'to' is required, making 'to be' the correct form. 'That he is' is wrong because inserting 'that he is' produces 'The CEO is thought that he is considering retirement,' which is ungrammatical — the personal passive construction cannot take a that-clause; only the impersonal version ('It is thought that he is considering') is valid with a that-clause, and that requires 'it' as the subject. 'Both A and C' is wrong because option C ('that he is') is grammatically impossible in this sentence structure, so only option A is correct.",category:"Grammar"},
  {id:"p5m2_5",question:"The figures are known _____ understated in the preliminary report.",options:["A) to be","B) to have been","C) being","D) to being"],answer:"B",explanation:"'To have been understated' is correct because the perfect passive infinitive is required when the reported situation (understatement) occurred before the current moment of knowing, expressing a past completed state relative to now. 'To be' is wrong because the simple passive infinitive 'to be understated' implies a present or ongoing state rather than something established before the current time. 'Being' is wrong because the bare present participle cannot follow a passive reporting verb; an infinitive construction is obligatory. 'To being' is wrong because 'to' as an infinitive marker must precede a base-form verb, not a gerund.",category:"Grammar"},
  {id:"p5m2_6",question:"_____ he had studied the market more carefully, he would not have made such a costly mistake.",options:["A) Unless","B) Provided","C) Had","D) If only"],answer:"C",explanation:"'Had he studied' is correct because in formal English, the third conditional can be expressed by inverting the auxiliary 'had' with the subject, omitting 'if' entirely; this is standard in written and literary registers. 'Unless' is wrong because 'unless' means 'except if' and creates an opposite logical meaning—'unless he had studied' would imply he did study, which contradicts the counterfactual scenario. 'Provided' is wrong because 'provided (that)' introduces a condition for a future or hypothetical event and cannot replace 'had' in a past counterfactual inversion. 'If only' is wrong because 'if only' expresses a wish or regret but cannot function as an inversion trigger to replace 'if had' in the conditional clause.",category:"Grammar"},
  {id:"p5m2_7",question:"_____ the team received more resources, the project could have been completed sooner.",options:["A) Should","B) Had","C) Were","D) Would"],answer:"B",explanation:"'Had the team received' is correct because it represents the inverted form of the third conditional ('If the team had received'), used when referring to a past hypothetical situation with 'would/could have + past participle' in the main clause. 'Should' is wrong because 'should + subject + base verb' is the inversion for a first conditional expressing a possibility in the future, not a past counterfactual. 'Were' is wrong because 'were + subject + infinitive' is the inversion for a second conditional expressing a hypothetical present or future situation, not a completed past one. 'Would' is wrong because 'would' belongs in the main (result) clause of a conditional, not in the if-clause.",category:"Grammar"},
  {id:"p5m2_8",question:"_____ she known about the conflict of interest, she would have recused herself.",options:["A) Were","B) Had","C) Should","D) If"],answer:"B",explanation:"'Had she known' is correct because it is the inverted third conditional structure equivalent to 'If she had known,' used to describe a past hypothetical situation where the condition was not met. 'Were' is wrong because 'were + subject + infinitive' is used for second conditional inversions involving hypothetical present or future states, not past knowledge. 'Should' is wrong because 'should + subject + infinitive' is a first conditional inversion used for future possibilities, not past counterfactuals. 'If' is wrong because while 'if she had known' is correct, 'If she known' (without 'had') is not grammatical, and 'if' alone cannot begin an inversion structure.",category:"Grammar"},
  {id:"p5m2_9",question:"_____ the regulations to change, the entire compliance framework would need revision.",options:["A) Should","B) Had","C) Were","D) Would"],answer:"C",explanation:"'Were the regulations to change' is correct because the 'were + subject + to + infinitive' inversion is the formal conditional structure used to present a hypothetical future event as a remote or uncertain possibility, paired with 'would' in the main clause. 'Should' is wrong because 'should + subject + base verb' implies a somewhat probable future condition, making it a different—less remote—conditional register than 'were to.' 'Had' is wrong because 'had + subject + past participle' is the third conditional inversion for past hypotheticals, not for future hypothetical events. 'Would' is wrong because 'would' belongs in the result (main) clause, not in the conditional clause.",category:"Grammar"},
  {id:"p5m2_10",question:"_____ you require further assistance, do not hesitate to contact our support team.",options:["A) Were","B) Should","C) Had","D) Would"],answer:"B",explanation:"'Should you require' is correct because the first conditional inversion 'should + subject + base verb' is used in formal and polite contexts to express a possible future condition, equivalent to 'If you should require.' 'Were' is wrong because 'were + subject + to + infinitive' conveys a more remote or hypothetical condition and is less natural in polite service-language contexts. 'Had' is wrong because 'had + subject + past participle' is the third conditional inversion for past counterfactuals and does not apply to a current or future assistance scenario. 'Would' is wrong because 'would' is used in the result clause of conditional sentences and cannot open a conditional if-clause.",category:"Grammar"},
  {id:"p5m2_11",question:"It is essential that the board _____ informed of any material changes immediately.",options:["A) is","B) be","C) was","D) were"],answer:"B",explanation:"'Be' is correct because after expressions of necessity such as 'it is essential that,' 'it is important that,' or 'it is vital that,' the verb in the subordinate clause must take the present subjunctive, which uses the base form of the verb for all persons and numbers. 'Is' is wrong because the indicative 'is' reflects a statement of fact, not the obligatory subjunctive mood required after necessity expressions. 'Was' is wrong because the past indicative 'was' is used for past factual statements and does not fulfill the subjunctive requirement in present necessity expressions. 'Were' is wrong because 'were' is the past subjunctive used in hypothetical or wish clauses (e.g., 'if it were'), not after present necessity expressions where the base form 'be' is required.",category:"Grammar"},
  {id:"p5m2_12",question:"The proposal requires that each applicant _____ a full business plan.",options:["A) submits","B) submit","C) submitted","D) will submit"],answer:"B",explanation:"'Submit' is correct because verbs of demand, requirement, and recommendation (require, insist, demand, recommend) trigger the mandative subjunctive in the that-clause, which uses the base form of the verb regardless of the subject. 'Submits' is wrong because the third-person singular indicative 'submits' does not satisfy the subjunctive requirement; the base form without the -s inflection must be used. 'Submitted' is wrong because the past tense 'submitted' is used for past factual statements and cannot fulfill the present mandative subjunctive. 'Will submit' is wrong because modal constructions are not used in subjunctive clauses; the base form without any modal is required.",category:"Grammar"},
  {id:"p5m2_13",question:"Management has suggested that all expenses _____ pre-approved before being incurred.",options:["A) are","B) were","C) be","D) will be"],answer:"C",explanation:"'Be' is correct because the verb 'suggest' (in the sense of a formal recommendation) triggers the mandative subjunctive in its that-clause, requiring the base form of the verb—here the passive base form 'be pre-approved.' 'Are' is wrong because the present indicative 'are' states a fact rather than a requirement, and does not fulfill the subjunctive mood required after 'suggest' used as a recommendation verb. 'Were' is wrong because the past indicative 'were' refers to a past factual condition and is not the correct subjunctive form after a present-tense recommendation verb. 'Will be' is wrong because modals are not used in mandative subjunctive clauses; the plain base form is obligatory.",category:"Grammar"},
  {id:"p5m2_14",question:"The auditors demanded that the records _____ made available for inspection.",options:["A) are","B) be","C) were","D) will be"],answer:"B",explanation:"'Be' is correct because 'demand' is a mandative verb that requires the subjunctive base form in the subordinate that-clause; the passive subjunctive here is 'be made available,' formed with the base form 'be' and the past participle 'made.' 'Are' is wrong because the indicative 'are' states a present fact and does not reflect the obligatory nature expressed by the mandative subjunctive after 'demanded.' 'Were' is wrong because the past indicative 'were' would describe a past factual situation, not the requirement conveyed by the subjunctive after a demand verb. 'Will be' is wrong because modal constructions are excluded from mandative subjunctive clauses; the base form must be used.",category:"Grammar"},
  {id:"p5m2_15",question:"The policy stipulates that every new hire _____ a background check before starting.",options:["A) undergoes","B) undergo","C) will undergo","D) has undergone"],answer:"B",explanation:"'Undergo' is correct because 'stipulate' is a mandative verb whose that-clause requires the present subjunctive base form, which does not add -s for third-person singular—thus 'every new hire undergo,' not 'undergoes.' 'Undergoes' is wrong because adding -s produces the indicative third-person singular, which is inappropriate after a mandative verb where the subjunctive base form is required. 'Will undergo' is wrong because modals are excluded from mandative subjunctive clauses, and the simple base form without a modal must be used. 'Has undergone' is wrong because the present perfect is an indicative tense and cannot serve as the mandative subjunctive required by 'stipulate.'",category:"Grammar"},
  {id:"p5m2_16",question:"What _____ is a complete overhaul of the current procurement process.",options:["A) is needed","B) needs","C) is necessary","D) both A and C"],answer:"D",explanation:"Both 'what is needed' and 'what is necessary' are correct because both form grammatically valid pseudo-cleft sentences where 'what' acts as a fused relative pronoun ('the thing that'), and the predicate noun after the main verb 'is' identifies what that thing is. Option A is correct because 'what is needed is a complete overhaul' is a standard pseudo-cleft where the passive 'is needed' fills the subject clause. Option C is correct because 'what is necessary is a complete overhaul' is equally valid, with 'is necessary' as the predicate of the what-clause. 'Needs' alone is wrong because 'what needs is' is not idiomatic; 'needs' requires a direct object ('what needs doing') or a different structure.",category:"Grammar"},
  {id:"p5m2_17",question:"It was the operations team _____ identified the flaw in the manufacturing process.",options:["A) that","B) which","C) who","D) both A and C"],answer:"D",explanation:"Both 'that' and 'who' are correct because in an it-cleft sentence ('It was + focused element + relative clause'), the relative pronoun 'that' is universal and can refer to people or things, while 'who' is also acceptable when the focused element is a person or group of people. Option A is correct because 'that' is the standard and most common choice in cleft sentences regardless of whether the focused element is animate or inanimate. Option C is correct because 'who' is permissible when the clefted element is a person or group (here, 'the operations team'), since the team is composed of people. 'Which' alone is wrong because 'which' is used to refer to non-human antecedents in defining relative clauses and is not the standard pronoun in cleft constructions referring to people.",category:"Grammar"},
  {id:"p5m2_18",question:"It was _____ during the audit _____ the discrepancies were first discovered.",options:["A) that / when","B) when / that","C) which / where","D) where / that"],answer:"B",explanation:"'When / that' is correct because this is a temporal it-cleft structure: 'It was when [time expression] that [main clause],' where 'when' introduces the adverbial time clause being focused, and 'that' is the obligatory connector that links the focused element to the rest of the sentence. 'That / when' is wrong because it reverses the roles, placing 'that' before the time expression and 'when' at the start of the main clause, which breaks the cleft pattern entirely. 'Which / where' is wrong because 'which' introduces a relative clause for a specific noun antecedent, and 'where' indicates place, neither of which fits the temporal focus of this sentence. 'Where / that' is wrong because 'where' signals location, not time, and cannot introduce the temporal adverbial ('during the audit') that is being focused in this cleft.",category:"Grammar"},
  {id:"p5m2_19",question:"_____ did impress the investors was the company's strong cash flow position.",options:["A) That","B) What","C) Which","D) How"],answer:"B",explanation:"'What' is correct because this is a pseudo-cleft (wh-cleft) sentence in which 'what' functions as a fused relative pronoun meaning 'the thing that,' creating a subject noun clause ('what did impress the investors') that is equated with the predicate noun ('the company's strong cash flow position'). 'That' is wrong because 'that' introduces a content clause as a complement or subject, but 'that did impress the investors was...' is not standard; 'that-clauses' used as subjects are rare and do not form the pseudo-cleft pattern. 'Which' is wrong because 'which' is a relative pronoun that must refer back to a specific previously mentioned noun antecedent, but there is no such antecedent here. 'How' is wrong because 'how' introduces manner or degree clauses and would produce 'how did impress the investors was,' which is grammatically incoherent.",category:"Grammar"},
  {id:"p5m2_20",question:"The thing _____ surprised analysts most was the size of the dividend increase.",options:["A) what","B) that","C) which","D) both B and C"],answer:"D",explanation:"Both 'that' and 'which' are correct because 'the thing' is a definite antecedent noun, and defining relative clauses that restrict its meaning can use either 'that' or 'which' in standard English, though 'that' is more common in restrictive clauses. Option B is correct because 'that' is the preferred relative pronoun in defining (restrictive) relative clauses modifying nouns like 'the thing.' Option C is correct because 'which' is also grammatically acceptable in restrictive relative clauses, particularly in formal registers, when modifying an inanimate noun such as 'the thing.' 'What' is wrong because 'what' is a fused relative pronoun that cannot follow an explicit antecedent noun—it replaces 'the thing that,' not follows 'the thing.'",category:"Grammar"},
  {id:"p5m2_21",question:"The research _____ a clear link between employee engagement and productivity.",options:["A) establishes","B) demonstrates","C) reveals","D) all of the above"],answer:"D",explanation:"All three options are correct because 'establishes,' 'demonstrates,' and 'reveals' are all standard academic and business English verbs used to describe what research findings show, each with a slightly different nuance but all grammatically and semantically valid in this context. 'Establishes' is correct because it means the research proves or confirms the existence of a link as a fact. 'Demonstrates' is correct because it means the research shows evidence of the link through data or argument. 'Reveals' is correct because it means the research uncovers or discloses the link, often implying it was previously unknown.",category:"Vocabulary"},
  {id:"p5m2_22",question:"The firm has _____ significant market share since entering the sector five years ago.",options:["A) amassed","B) garnered","C) accumulated","D) all of the above"],answer:"D",explanation:"All three options are correct because 'amassed,' 'garnered,' and 'accumulated' all describe the process of building up a large quantity of something over time, and all collocate naturally with 'market share' in business English. 'Amassed' is correct because it suggests gathering a large amount, often implying speed or impressiveness. 'Garnered' is correct because it means to gather or acquire something through effort or merit, commonly used in formal business contexts. 'Accumulated' is correct because it emphasizes a gradual build-up over the five-year period mentioned in the sentence.",category:"Vocabulary"},
  {id:"p5m2_23",question:"The revised terms were _____ acceptable to both parties following a second round of negotiations.",options:["A) deemed","B) considered","C) found","D) all of the above"],answer:"D",explanation:"All three options are correct because 'deemed,' 'considered,' and 'found' are all linking verbs or passive constructions that can precede an adjective complement ('acceptable') to describe the judgment reached about the revised terms. 'Deemed' is correct because it is a formal verb meaning officially judged or regarded, very common in legal and business contexts. 'Considered' is correct because it means regarded as after evaluation, fitting the context of post-negotiation assessment. 'Found' is correct because in the passive ('were found acceptable'), it describes the conclusion reached after examination or discussion.",category:"Vocabulary"},
  {id:"p5m2_24",question:"The proposal was _____ favorably by the selection committee.",options:["A) received","B) viewed","C) regarded","D) all of the above"],answer:"D",explanation:"All three options are correct because 'received,' 'viewed,' and 'regarded' all collocate with 'favorably' to indicate that the selection committee responded positively to the proposal, each verb emphasizing a slightly different aspect of evaluation. 'Received favorably' is correct because it is a standard idiom meaning the proposal was met with a positive reaction. 'Viewed favorably' is correct because it means it was seen or assessed positively, a natural collocation in formal evaluation contexts. 'Regarded favorably' is correct because it means it was held in high esteem or considered positively, equally natural in committee or review contexts.",category:"Vocabulary"},
  {id:"p5m2_25",question:"The management team has _____ a comprehensive strategy to improve customer retention.",options:["A) put forward","B) proposed","C) outlined","D) all of the above"],answer:"D",explanation:"All three options are correct because 'put forward,' 'proposed,' and 'outlined' all describe actions of presenting or introducing a strategy to an audience, which is the meaning required in this sentence. 'Put forward' is correct because it means to present or submit something for consideration, a common phrasal verb in formal business English. 'Proposed' is correct because it means formally suggested or recommended the strategy, implying it may still require approval. 'Outlined' is correct because it means described the main features or structure of the strategy, emphasizing the presentation of key points.",category:"Vocabulary"},
  {id:"p5m2_26",question:"The company _____ all legal requirements before launching the product overseas.",options:["A) ascertained","B) verified","C) confirmed","D) all of the above"],answer:"D",explanation:"All three options are correct because 'ascertained,' 'verified,' and 'confirmed' all mean to establish the truth or accuracy of something through investigation, all of which are appropriate for checking legal compliance before a product launch. 'Ascertained' is correct because it means found out or established with certainty, often through investigation or inquiry. 'Verified' is correct because it means confirmed the accuracy or truth of something, with a strong implication of checking against a standard or evidence. 'Confirmed' is correct because it means established or made certain, commonly used in business and legal contexts when requirements are checked and found to be met.",category:"Vocabulary"},
  {id:"p5m2_27",question:"The regulatory environment has _____ significantly in the past decade.",options:["A) evolved","B) changed","C) shifted","D) all of the above"],answer:"D",explanation:"All three options are correct because 'evolved,' 'changed,' and 'shifted' all describe meaningful transformation in the regulatory environment over time, each with a slightly different connotation. 'Evolved' is correct because it implies gradual, progressive development, which suits a decade-long transformation. 'Changed' is correct because it is the most general term for becoming different, grammatically and semantically natural with 'significantly.' 'Shifted' is correct because it implies a directional or notable movement, often used when describing a change in emphasis, focus, or approach in regulatory contexts.",category:"Vocabulary"},
  {id:"p5m2_28",question:"She _____ a key role in negotiating the landmark trade agreement.",options:["A) played","B) took","C) assumed","D) all of the above"],answer:"D",explanation:"All three options are correct because 'played,' 'took,' and 'assumed' are all standard collocations with 'a key role' in English, each describing the act of taking on an important function. 'Played a key role' is correct because it is the most idiomatic and widely used collocation to describe contributing actively to an outcome. 'Took a key role' is correct because 'take a role' is a natural expression meaning to accept or perform a particular function. 'Assumed a key role' is correct because 'assume a role' means to take on responsibility for it, carrying a formal tone appropriate in business contexts.",category:"Vocabulary"},
  {id:"p5m2_29",question:"The new system is designed to _____ errors during the data entry process.",options:["A) minimize","B) reduce","C) eliminate","D) all of the above"],answer:"D",explanation:"All three options are correct because 'minimize,' 'reduce,' and 'eliminate' are all valid objectives for a data entry system, progressing from limiting errors to a low level, to removing them entirely. 'Minimize' is correct because it means to reduce something to the smallest possible amount, a realistic and common design goal for data systems. 'Reduce' is correct because it is the most general term for making the number of errors smaller, naturally collocating with 'errors.' 'Eliminate' is correct because it means to remove entirely, representing the most ambitious goal, and is a standard term in process improvement language.",category:"Vocabulary"},
  {id:"p5m2_30",question:"The board _____ the new strategic direction at the extraordinary general meeting.",options:["A) ratified","B) endorsed","C) approved","D) all of the above"],answer:"D",explanation:"All three options are correct because 'ratified,' 'endorsed,' and 'approved' all describe the board giving formal acceptance or agreement to the new strategic direction. 'Ratified' is correct because it means to give formal or official sanction to a decision, often implying a voting procedure. 'Endorsed' is correct because it means to declare support or approval for the direction, with a connotation of public backing. 'Approved' is correct because it is the most general term for formally agreeing to or accepting the strategic direction, standard in board decision-making contexts.",category:"Vocabulary"},
  {id:"p5m2_31",question:"The team's performance has _____ everyone's expectations this quarter.",options:["A) exceeded","B) surpassed","C) outperformed","D) all of the above"],answer:"D",explanation:"All three options are correct because 'exceeded,' 'surpassed,' and 'outperformed' all describe performance that went beyond expectations, and all collocate naturally with 'expectations' in business English. 'Exceeded' is correct because it is the standard and most common verb used with 'expectations' to indicate performance beyond what was anticipated. 'Surpassed' is correct because it means to go beyond in quality or quantity, a near-synonym of 'exceeded' commonly used in formal business reporting. 'Outperformed' is correct because it means to perform better than a benchmark or expectation, widely used in performance evaluation and financial contexts.",category:"Vocabulary"},
  {id:"p5m2_32",question:"The factory has _____ production capacity by 40% following the equipment upgrade.",options:["A) expanded","B) increased","C) boosted","D) all of the above"],answer:"D",explanation:"All three options are correct because 'expanded,' 'increased,' and 'boosted' all describe a growth in production capacity and all collocate naturally with 'production capacity' in manufacturing and business contexts. 'Expanded' is correct because it implies a widening or extension of capacity, natural when describing physical or operational growth after an upgrade. 'Increased' is correct because it is the most neutral and widely used term for making something larger, directly pairing with the percentage figure '40%.' 'Boosted' is correct because it conveys a positive, often significant, upward change and is common in business and operational reporting.",category:"Vocabulary"},
  {id:"p5m2_33",question:"The company has _____ a new digital platform to serve its growing customer base.",options:["A) launched","B) rolled out","C) deployed","D) all of the above"],answer:"D",explanation:"All three options are correct because 'launched,' 'rolled out,' and 'deployed' all describe the act of making a new digital platform available to users, each with a slightly different nuance drawn from business and technology language. 'Launched' is correct because it means to introduce a product or service to the market, the most common term for releasing a new platform. 'Rolled out' is correct because it is a phrasal verb meaning to introduce something gradually or in stages, often used for technology platforms serving large user bases. 'Deployed' is correct because it is a technical and business term meaning to put a system into active use, especially in IT and software contexts.",category:"Vocabulary"},
  {id:"p5m2_34",question:"The consultant _____ that the company restructure its sales division.",options:["A) advised","B) recommended","C) suggested","D) all of the above"],answer:"D",explanation:"All three options are correct because 'advised,' 'recommended,' and 'suggested' are all mandative verbs that can be followed by a that-clause with a subjunctive base verb ('restructure'), and all describe the consultant offering professional guidance. 'Advised' is correct because it means to give professional counsel, and 'advised that + subjunctive' is grammatically standard. 'Recommended' is correct because it means to formally suggest as a best course of action, also followed by 'that + subjunctive.' 'Suggested' is correct because it means to put forward an idea for consideration, equally triggering the mandative subjunctive in the that-clause.",category:"Vocabulary"},
  {id:"p5m2_35",question:"The company has _____ new policies to address gender diversity at the board level.",options:["A) introduced","B) implemented","C) put in place","D) all of the above"],answer:"D",explanation:"All three options are correct because 'introduced,' 'implemented,' and 'put in place' all describe the act of establishing new policies, each emphasizing a slightly different stage or aspect of the process. 'Introduced' is correct because it means to bring something new into use or existence for the first time, appropriate for new diversity policies. 'Implemented' is correct because it means to put a plan or policy into action, emphasizing execution rather than just announcement. 'Put in place' is correct because it is an idiomatic expression meaning to establish or create a system or measure, widely used in formal business English.",category:"Vocabulary"},
  {id:"p5m2_36",question:"Her _____ to the project contributed greatly to its early completion.",options:["A) dedication","B) commitment","C) contribution","D) all of the above"],answer:"D",explanation:"All three options are correct because 'dedication,' 'commitment,' and 'contribution' can all serve as the subject noun that 'contributed greatly to' the early completion, as each describes a positive quality or input relevant to project success. 'Dedication' is correct because it refers to her devoted effort and focus, which naturally 'contributed greatly' to the outcome. 'Commitment' is correct because it describes her firm pledge or resolve to the project, which equally led to early completion. 'Contribution' is correct because it refers directly to her input or work, making 'her contribution contributed greatly' a valid if slightly repetitive collocation.",category:"Vocabulary"},
  {id:"p5m2_37",question:"The company's _____ has been built on a foundation of transparency and integrity.",options:["A) reputation","B) standing","C) credibility","D) all of the above"],answer:"D",explanation:"All three options are correct because 'reputation,' 'standing,' and 'credibility' all refer to how an organization is perceived by others, and all can be 'built on a foundation of' positive values like transparency and integrity. 'Reputation' is correct because it means the general opinion held about a company's character, the most common noun used with 'built on.' 'Standing' is correct because it means a company's status or rank in relation to others, appropriate in formal business contexts. 'Credibility' is correct because it refers to the quality of being trusted and believed, directly linked to transparency and integrity as foundational values.",category:"Vocabulary"},
  {id:"p5m2_38",question:"The partnership agreement includes a clause that _____ both parties to mediation before litigation.",options:["A) requires","B) obligates","C) compels","D) all of the above"],answer:"D",explanation:"All three options are correct because 'requires,' 'obligates,' and 'compels' all mean to make something mandatory for both parties, and all are followed by an object plus an infinitive ('requires both parties to'), which fits the sentence structure. 'Requires' is correct because it is the most common formal verb for making something a legal or contractual necessity. 'Obligates' is correct because it means to bind someone to a duty, particularly common in legal and contractual language. 'Compels' is correct because it means to force or necessitate an action, appropriate in the context of a binding clause in an agreement.",category:"Vocabulary"},
  {id:"p5m2_39",question:"The market study _____ that demand for the product will triple within five years.",options:["A) projects","B) forecasts","C) predicts","D) all of the above"],answer:"D",explanation:"All three options are correct because 'projects,' 'forecasts,' and 'predicts' are all standard forward-looking verbs that introduce a that-clause describing a future expectation based on data or analysis. 'Projects' is correct because it is widely used in business and finance to mean making a calculation or estimate about the future, especially based on current trends. 'Forecasts' is correct because it means to estimate or predict future trends using data, commonly used in market analysis. 'Predicts' is correct because it means to state what is expected to happen in the future, appropriate for reporting market study conclusions.",category:"Vocabulary"},
  {id:"p5m2_40",question:"The committee will _____ each proposal on its merits before making a final recommendation.",options:["A) evaluate","B) assess","C) appraise","D) all of the above"],answer:"D",explanation:"All three options are correct because 'evaluate,' 'assess,' and 'appraise' all mean to judge the value, quality, or merits of something, and all naturally take a proposal as their object. 'Evaluate' is correct because it means to form a careful judgment about the value or significance of something, the most common term in formal committee contexts. 'Assess' is correct because it means to estimate or judge the worth of something, particularly after examination of evidence or criteria. 'Appraise' is correct because it means to assess the value or quality of something in detail, often with professional judgment, commonly used in business and financial contexts.",category:"Vocabulary"},
  {id:"p5m2_41",question:"The team could not _____ on the best approach, causing delays.",options:["A) settle","B) agree","C) decide","D) all of the above"],answer:"D",explanation:"All three options are correct because 'settle on,' 'agree on,' and 'decide on' all describe the act of reaching a conclusion or consensus, and all use the preposition 'on' to link to the subject of discussion. 'Settle on' is correct because it means to choose or agree upon something after consideration, commonly used when a group arrives at a decision. 'Agree on' is correct because it means to reach a shared conclusion or consensus, the most direct expression of the meaning intended. 'Decide on' is correct because it means to make a firm choice about something, which captures the same idea of reaching a conclusion on the best approach.",category:"Vocabulary"},
  {id:"p5m2_42",question:"The director _____ the new initiative at the quarterly town hall.",options:["A) unveiled","B) announced","C) introduced","D) all of the above"],answer:"D",explanation:"All three options are correct because 'unveiled,' 'announced,' and 'introduced' all describe the act of revealing or presenting something new to an audience at a formal event. 'Unveiled' is correct because it means to reveal something publicly for the first time, often used for significant or notable announcements with an element of drama. 'Announced' is correct because it means to make a public declaration, the most neutral and general of the three options. 'Introduced' is correct because it means to present something new formally, appropriate for an initiative being presented for the first time at a company-wide event.",category:"Vocabulary"},
  {id:"p5m2_43",question:"The management team has _____ to review the entire compensation structure.",options:["A) decided","B) resolved","C) committed","D) all of the above"],answer:"D",explanation:"All three options are correct because 'decided,' 'resolved,' and 'committed' all describe management forming a firm intention to carry out the review, and all are followed by an infinitive ('to review'). 'Decided' is correct because it means reached a conclusion after deliberation, naturally paired with an infinitive to state what was decided. 'Resolved' is correct because it means made a firm decision or determination, carrying a slightly more formal or emphatic tone than 'decided.' 'Committed' is correct because it means made a pledge or binding obligation, emphasizing accountability and follow-through.",category:"Vocabulary"},
  {id:"p5m2_44",question:"The acquisition is expected to _____ significant operational synergies.",options:["A) generate","B) create","C) unlock","D) all of the above"],answer:"D",explanation:"All three options are correct because 'generate,' 'create,' and 'unlock' are all standard verbs used in mergers-and-acquisitions language to describe how a deal produces synergies. 'Generate' is correct because it means to produce or bring about, a common term in financial forecasting contexts. 'Create' is correct because it is the most general term for bringing something into existence, widely used with 'synergies' in business reporting. 'Unlock' is correct because it carries the implication of releasing latent or hidden value, a particularly popular metaphor in M&A and investment analysis language.",category:"Vocabulary"},
  {id:"p5m2_45",question:"The new director will _____ responsibility for the company's global supply chain.",options:["A) take","B) assume","C) shoulder","D) all of the above"],answer:"D",explanation:"All three options are correct because 'take,' 'assume,' and 'shoulder' are all idiomatic collocations with 'responsibility' that describe accepting or bearing accountability for a function or role. 'Take responsibility' is correct because it is the most common and versatile collocation, meaning to accept or accept the duty. 'Assume responsibility' is correct because it means to formally take on a duty or role, with a slightly more formal register common in business and official contexts. 'Shoulder responsibility' is correct because it is a metaphorical expression meaning to bear the burden of a duty, emphasizing the weight of the obligation.",category:"Vocabulary"},
  {id:"p5m2_46",question:"The firm has been able to _____ its market position despite intense competition.",options:["A) maintain","B) sustain","C) hold","D) all of the above"],answer:"D",explanation:"All three options are correct because 'maintain,' 'sustain,' and 'hold' all describe the action of keeping a market position at the same level despite external pressure. 'Maintain' is correct because it is the most common verb for keeping something at an existing level, naturally collocating with 'market position.' 'Sustain' is correct because it implies continued effort to keep something going over time, appropriate for the ongoing challenge of competition. 'Hold' is correct because it means to keep or retain possession of something, a natural business English collocation with 'market position.'",category:"Vocabulary"},
  {id:"p5m2_47",question:"The audit found that internal controls were _____ in several key areas.",options:["A) inadequate","B) deficient","C) lacking","D) all of the above"],answer:"D",explanation:"All three options are correct because 'inadequate,' 'deficient,' and 'lacking' all describe internal controls that fall short of the required standard and are all appropriate in the context of audit findings. 'Inadequate' is correct because it means not sufficient or suitable for the purpose, a standard adjective in audit and compliance language. 'Deficient' is correct because it means falling short of a required level, often used in regulatory and audit reports to describe shortcomings. 'Lacking' is correct because it means absent or insufficient, functioning as a predicate adjective after a linking verb ('were lacking'), naturally describing a gap in controls.",category:"Vocabulary"},
  {id:"p5m2_48",question:"The company _____ a strong balance sheet with minimal debt.",options:["A) maintains","B) boasts","C) carries","D) all of the above"],answer:"D",explanation:"All three options are correct because 'maintains,' 'boasts,' and 'carries' all collocate with 'a strong balance sheet' in standard financial English. 'Maintains' is correct because it means to keep something at a particular level, implying ongoing effort to preserve the financial strength. 'Boasts' is correct because it means to proudly possess a notable quality, often used in corporate communications to highlight a positive attribute. 'Carries' is correct because in financial language 'to carry a balance sheet' means to have or hold a particular financial position, a natural technical collocation.",category:"Vocabulary"},
  {id:"p5m2_49",question:"The merger is _____ to create over 1,000 new jobs in the region.",options:["A) projected","B) expected","C) estimated","D) all of the above"],answer:"D",explanation:"All three options are correct because 'projected,' 'expected,' and 'estimated' are all passive adjectives that introduce a forward-looking infinitive ('to create') and are used to express anticipated outcomes based on analysis. 'Projected' is correct because it means calculated or forecast from data, standard in financial and economic reporting about future outcomes. 'Expected' is correct because it is the most general and widely used term for stating what is anticipated, natural in news and corporate announcements. 'Estimated' is correct because it means approximately calculated or reckoned, appropriate when the job creation figure is based on a calculation or approximation.",category:"Vocabulary"},
  {id:"p5m2_50",question:"The sales team was _____ after closing the largest deal in company history.",options:["A) elated","B) thrilled","C) delighted","D) all of the above"],answer:"D",explanation:"All three options are correct because 'elated,' 'thrilled,' and 'delighted' are all adjectives expressing intense happiness or excitement and all naturally follow the linking verb 'was' to describe the team's emotional state. 'Elated' is correct because it means extremely happy and proud, often implying a sense of triumph, appropriate after a record-breaking achievement. 'Thrilled' is correct because it means excited and pleased, a common and natural adjective in both formal and informal business contexts. 'Delighted' is correct because it means very pleased, slightly more formal than 'thrilled,' and commonly used in business English to describe a strong positive reaction.",category:"Vocabulary"},
  {id:"p5m2_51",question:"The company's rapid expansion _____ its ability to maintain quality standards.",options:["A) challenged","B) tested","C) strained","D) all of the above"],answer:"D",explanation:"All three options are correct because 'challenged,' 'tested,' and 'strained' all describe the pressure that rapid expansion placed on the company's ability to maintain quality, each with a slightly different intensity. 'Challenged' is correct because it means put under pressure or made difficult, the most neutral description of the impact of growth on quality. 'Tested' is correct because it means put to a severe trial, implying that the ability to maintain quality was pushed to its limits. 'Strained' is correct because it means stretched to the point of difficulty or potential failure, implying the most severe level of pressure among the three options.",category:"Vocabulary"},
  {id:"p5m2_52",question:"She is _____ as one of the most influential figures in the technology industry.",options:["A) recognized","B) regarded","C) considered","D) all of the above"],answer:"D",explanation:"All three options are correct because 'recognized,' 'regarded,' and 'considered' are all standard verbs used in the passive to describe how a person is perceived or acknowledged by others, each followed by 'as.' 'Recognized as' is correct because it means publicly acknowledged to be something, often implying a formal or widespread acknowledgment. 'Regarded as' is correct because it means generally viewed or considered to be something, commonly used in both formal writing and journalism. 'Considered as' is correct because it means deemed or judged to be something by others; while 'considered' more commonly appears without 'as' in formal writing ('is considered one of'), 'considered as' is widely used in international and journalistic English and is accepted as a valid construction in this context.",category:"Vocabulary"},
  {id:"p5m2_53",question:"The board _____ the acquisition offer, citing concerns about valuation.",options:["A) rejected","B) declined","C) turned down","D) all of the above"],answer:"D",explanation:"All three options are correct because 'rejected,' 'declined,' and 'turned down' all mean to refuse or say no to an offer, and all are standard collocations with 'acquisition offer' in business English. 'Rejected' is correct because it means to dismiss something as not acceptable, often carrying a definitive or formal tone used in board decisions. 'Declined' is correct because it means politely or formally refused, a slightly softer term that can imply the refusal was courteous rather than hostile. 'Turned down' is correct because it is a common phrasal verb meaning to refuse an offer, natural in both formal and informal business English.",category:"Vocabulary"},
  {id:"p5m2_54",question:"The new marketing strategy has _____ a significant improvement in brand awareness.",options:["A) produced","B) generated","C) led to","D) all of the above"],answer:"D",explanation:"All three options are correct because 'produced,' 'generated,' and 'led to' all describe the new marketing strategy as the cause of an improvement in brand awareness, each expressing a causal relationship. 'Produced' is correct because it means brought about a result, natural when describing a strategy's tangible output. 'Generated' is correct because it means caused or created something, widely used in business contexts to describe the effects of marketing activity. 'Led to' is correct because it is a phrasal verb meaning resulted in, describing the strategy as the cause that led to the outcome of improved awareness.",category:"Vocabulary"},
  {id:"p5m2_55",question:"The company has _____ its environmental impact by switching to renewable energy.",options:["A) reduced","B) minimized","C) cut","D) all of the above"],answer:"D",explanation:"All three options are correct because 'reduced,' 'minimized,' and 'cut' all describe a decrease in environmental impact and all collocate naturally with 'environmental impact' in sustainability reporting. 'Reduced' is correct because it is the most general and neutral verb for making something smaller, widely used in environmental and corporate sustainability language. 'Minimized' is correct because it means lowered to the smallest possible amount, implying a strong commitment to reducing impact as much as possible. 'Cut' is correct because it is a direct and emphatic verb meaning to reduce significantly, common in both informal and formal business communication about environmental targets.",category:"Vocabulary"},
  {id:"p5m2_56",question:"The HR team will _____ exit interviews with all departing employees.",options:["A) conduct","B) carry out","C) hold","D) all of the above"],answer:"D",explanation:"All three options are correct because 'conduct,' 'carry out,' and 'hold' are all standard collocations with 'interviews' in formal business English, each describing the act of performing or organizing the interview process. 'Conduct' is correct because it is the most common formal verb for performing structured activities like interviews, meetings, or research. 'Carry out' is correct because it is a phrasal verb meaning to perform or complete a task, natural in HR and operational contexts. 'Hold' is correct because it means to organize and run an event or meeting, and 'hold interviews' is a well-established business English collocation.",category:"Vocabulary"},
  {id:"p5m2_57",question:"The company's digital transformation has been _____ by strong leadership.",options:["A) driven","B) powered","C) enabled","D) all of the above"],answer:"D",explanation:"All three options are correct because 'driven,' 'powered,' and 'enabled' are all past participles that can follow 'has been' in a passive construction to describe the role that strong leadership has played in the digital transformation. 'Driven' is correct because it means propelled or motivated, a common passive construction when describing a key force behind an initiative. 'Powered' is correct because it is a metaphorical term meaning energized or fueled, widely used in business and technology contexts to describe what drives a process. 'Enabled' is correct because it means made possible, emphasizing that leadership created the conditions or removed barriers for the transformation to succeed.",category:"Vocabulary"},
  {id:"p5m2_58",question:"Management _____ the importance of maintaining open communication with staff.",options:["A) stressed","B) emphasized","C) underlined","D) all of the above"],answer:"D",explanation:"All three options are correct because 'stressed,' 'emphasized,' and 'underlined' are all synonymous verbs meaning to draw special attention to the importance of something, all of which are standard in formal business communication. 'Stressed' is correct because it means to highlight or give special weight to something, a common verb in both spoken and written business English. 'Emphasized' is correct because it means to give particular importance to something, slightly more formal and widely used in business writing. 'Underlined' is correct because it means to draw attention to or reinforce the significance of something, a metaphorical extension of the literal meaning of underlining text.",category:"Vocabulary"},
  {id:"p5m2_59",question:"The team leader was _____ for her ability to motivate staff under pressure.",options:["A) praised","B) commended","C) recognized","D) all of the above"],answer:"D",explanation:"All three options are correct because 'praised,' 'commended,' and 'recognized' are all passive adjectives followed by 'for' that describe receiving positive acknowledgment for a specific quality or achievement. 'Praised for' is correct because it means given approval or admiration for something, the most common and general expression of positive feedback. 'Commended for' is correct because it means formally or officially praised for something, carrying a slightly more official or ceremonial tone. 'Recognized for' is correct because it means publicly acknowledged or given credit for something, widely used in performance management and awards contexts.",category:"Vocabulary"},
  {id:"p5m2_60",question:"The vendor _____ to deliver the components on time, causing production delays.",options:["A) failed","B) was unable","C) could not","D) all of the above"],answer:"D",explanation:"All three options are correct because 'failed to deliver,' 'was unable to deliver,' and 'could not deliver' all express the same outcome—the vendor did not deliver on time—using three different grammatical constructions. 'Failed to deliver' is correct because it uses the verb 'fail + infinitive' to describe not fulfilling an obligation, the most formal and common choice in business reporting. 'Was unable to deliver' is correct because it uses the modal-like adjective 'unable + infinitive' to describe a lack of ability, slightly less blunt than 'failed.' 'Could not deliver' is correct because it uses the modal 'could not + base verb' to describe an incapacity in the past, a natural and neutral alternative in this context.",category:"Vocabulary"},
  {id:"p5m2_61",question:"The company has _____ to become the market leader in sustainable packaging.",options:["A) aspired","B) aimed","C) set out","D) all of the above"],answer:"D",explanation:"All three options are correct because 'aspired,' 'aimed,' and 'set out' all describe the company having an ambition or goal expressed through an infinitive, and all are standard in formal business English. 'Aspired to become' is correct because 'aspire + to + infinitive' means to have a strong desire or ambition to achieve something, appropriate for a long-term strategic goal. 'Aimed to become' is correct because 'aim + to + infinitive' means to have as an objective, widely used in business strategy contexts. 'Set out to become' is correct because 'set out + to + infinitive' means to begin with the intention of achieving something, implying deliberate and intentional action.",category:"Vocabulary"},
  {id:"p5m2_62",question:"The operations team _____ a thorough review of the logistics network.",options:["A) undertook","B) conducted","C) carried out","D) all of the above"],answer:"D",explanation:"All three options are correct because 'undertook,' 'conducted,' and 'carried out' are all past-tense verbs that collocate naturally with 'a review' to describe the act of performing a thorough examination. 'Undertook' is correct because it is the past tense of 'undertake,' meaning to begin or commit to performing a task, often implying a significant or formal effort. 'Conducted' is correct because it means performed or organized in a systematic and professional manner, the most formal of the three and widely used in business and academic contexts. 'Carried out' is correct because it is a phrasal verb meaning to perform or complete a task, natural in operational and project management contexts.",category:"Vocabulary"},
  {id:"p5m2_63",question:"The contract was _____ following a breach of the non-disclosure agreement.",options:["A) terminated","B) voided","C) cancelled","D) all of the above"],answer:"D",explanation:"All three options are correct because 'terminated,' 'voided,' and 'cancelled' are all legal terms that describe ending a contract, each with a slightly different legal implication. 'Terminated' is correct because it means brought to an end, often implying that one party exercised a right to end the contract due to a breach or other legal trigger. 'Voided' is correct because it means declared legally null and of no effect, often implying the contract is treated as if it never existed due to a fundamental breach. 'Cancelled' is correct because it means called off or annulled, the most general term for ending a contract, appropriate in both formal and informal business contexts.",category:"Vocabulary"},
  {id:"p5m2_64",question:"The new pricing model _____ better value for money for enterprise clients.",options:["A) offers","B) provides","C) delivers","D) all of the above"],answer:"D",explanation:"All three options are correct because 'offers,' 'provides,' and 'delivers' all describe a pricing model making value available to clients, each with a slightly different emphasis but all standard collocations with 'value for money.' 'Offers' is correct because it means makes something available to someone, appropriate when describing what a model or product presents to customers. 'Provides' is correct because it means supplies or makes available, the most neutral and frequently used term in this context. 'Delivers' is correct because it means produces or yields a result, often used in business English to emphasize the concrete realization of a benefit such as value for money.",category:"Vocabulary"},
  {id:"p5m2_65",question:"The CEO's vision has _____ a culture of innovation throughout the organization.",options:["A) fostered","B) cultivated","C) encouraged","D) all of the above"],answer:"D",explanation:"All three options are correct because 'fostered,' 'cultivated,' and 'encouraged' all describe the CEO's vision actively developing or supporting a culture of innovation across the organization. 'Fostered' is correct because it means promoted the development of something, particularly used for nurturing qualities, behaviors, or cultures over time. 'Cultivated' is correct because it means carefully developed or grown, drawing on an agricultural metaphor to suggest deliberate and sustained effort to develop a culture. 'Encouraged' is correct because it means promoted or supported, the most general of the three, natural when describing leadership behavior that promotes a desirable organizational trait.",category:"Vocabulary"},
  {id:"p5m2_66",question:"The report _____ that cost-cutting measures had a negative impact on quality.",options:["A) indicated","B) showed","C) found","D) all of the above"],answer:"D",explanation:"All three options are correct because 'indicated,' 'showed,' and 'found' are all reporting verbs used to introduce the conclusions or evidence of a report, all followed by a that-clause. 'Indicated' is correct because it means provided a sign or suggestion of, often used when results point to a conclusion without being entirely definitive. 'Showed' is correct because it means demonstrated by evidence or data, the most direct and common reporting verb in this context. 'Found' is correct because it means concluded or discovered through investigation, commonly used in formal reports to state the outcome of an analysis.",category:"Vocabulary"},
  {id:"p5m2_67",question:"The partnership is _____ on both parties fulfilling their agreed obligations.",options:["A) conditional","B) contingent","C) dependent","D) all of the above"],answer:"D",explanation:"All three options are correct because 'conditional on,' 'contingent on,' and 'dependent on' all express that the partnership requires both parties to fulfil their obligations, describing a state of dependency or prerequisite condition. 'Conditional on' is correct because it means existing or valid only if a specified requirement is met, a standard legal and business English expression. 'Contingent on' is correct because it means depending on the occurrence of something, widely used in contracts and formal agreements. 'Dependent on' is correct because it means relying on or determined by something, the most general of the three, natural in describing conditions of a partnership.",category:"Vocabulary"},
  {id:"p5m2_68",question:"Efforts to _____ the company's debt have been largely successful.",options:["A) reduce","B) pay down","C) deleverage","D) all of the above"],answer:"D",explanation:"All three options are correct because 'reduce,' 'pay down,' and 'deleverage' all describe the process of decreasing the company's debt burden, each drawn from different levels of financial language formality. 'Reduce' is correct because it is the most general term for making something smaller, widely applicable in financial and operational contexts. 'Pay down' is correct because it is a phrasal verb specifically meaning to repay or reduce the principal of a debt, natural in both informal and formal business English. 'Deleverage' is correct because it is a technical financial term meaning to reduce the ratio of debt to equity or assets, common in investment analysis and corporate finance.",category:"Vocabulary"},
  {id:"p5m2_69",question:"The analyst _____ the company's growth trajectory as 'sustainable and robust'.",options:["A) described","B) characterized","C) labeled","D) all of the above"],answer:"D",explanation:"All three options are correct because 'described,' 'characterized,' and 'labeled' are all reporting verbs that introduce a quoted or paraphrased assessment, each followed by 'as' to link the subject to the analyst's description. 'Described as' is correct because it is the most neutral and common reporting verb, appropriate for conveying any kind of commentary or assessment. 'Characterized as' is correct because it means described in terms of key qualities or features, slightly more analytical in tone and common in financial and academic reporting. 'Labeled as' is correct because it means given a specific designation or category, appropriate when the analyst assigns a particular descriptor to the growth trajectory.",category:"Vocabulary"},
  {id:"p5m2_70",question:"The supplier has _____ its manufacturing capacity by opening a second facility.",options:["A) increased","B) expanded","C) doubled","D) both A and B"],answer:"D",explanation:"'Increased' and 'expanded' are both correct because both verbs describe a growth in manufacturing capacity and are accurate regardless of the exact amount of increase, unlike 'doubled' which would only be correct if the capacity specifically grew by 100%. 'Increased' is correct because it is the most general and neutral term for making something larger, with no implication about the degree of growth. 'Expanded' is correct because it implies a widening or extension of capacity, naturally collocating with 'manufacturing capacity' in business reporting. 'Doubled' is wrong in this context because the sentence does not specify that capacity grew by exactly 100%, making 'doubled' potentially inaccurate without additional evidence.",category:"Vocabulary"},
  {id:"p5m2_71",question:"The new compliance framework _____ all previous guidelines and replaces them.",options:["A) supersedes","B) replaces","C) overrides","D) all of the above"],answer:"D",explanation:"All three options are correct because 'supersedes,' 'replaces,' and 'overrides' all describe the new framework taking precedence over or taking the place of all previous guidelines, all standard in legal and regulatory language. 'Supersedes' is correct because it is the most formal and precise legal term meaning to take the place of something by virtue of superior authority or more recent status. 'Replaces' is correct because it means to take the place of something else; although the word 'replaces' also appears in the second clause ('and replaces them'), the blank and the clause serve different grammatical roles — the blank fills the main predicate while the second clause reinforces the meaning with the object 'them,' making the repetition acceptable as a stylistic emphasis. 'Overrides' is correct because it means to take priority over or nullify something else, particularly appropriate in regulatory and legal contexts where a newer rule cancels out older ones.",category:"Vocabulary"},
  {id:"p5m2_72",question:"The company _____ all necessary permits before breaking ground on the new facility.",options:["A) obtained","B) secured","C) acquired","D) all of the above"],answer:"D",explanation:"All three options are correct because 'obtained,' 'secured,' and 'acquired' all describe the act of getting or gaining the necessary permits, all natural collocations in business and construction contexts. 'Obtained' is correct because it is the most general and neutral term for successfully getting something, widely used in formal and legal contexts. 'Secured' is correct because it implies making certain of getting something, often after effort or negotiation, a common term in project management language. 'Acquired' is correct because it means to come into possession of something, natural in formal business English when describing gaining licenses, permits, or rights.",category:"Vocabulary"},
  {id:"p5m2_73",question:"The board will _____ a decision about the executive compensation plan next week.",options:["A) reach","B) make","C) arrive at","D) all of the above"],answer:"D",explanation:"All three options are correct because 'reach a decision,' 'make a decision,' and 'arrive at a decision' are all standard collocations in English meaning to conclude a process of deliberation by choosing a course of action. 'Reach a decision' is correct because it is a natural collocation emphasizing the conclusion of a deliberative process, common in formal business contexts. 'Make a decision' is correct because it is the most common and versatile collocation, widely used in everyday and formal business English. 'Arrive at a decision' is correct because it is a phrasal collocation implying a process of reasoning or discussion that leads to a final conclusion, appropriate in formal board or committee contexts.",category:"Vocabulary"},
  {id:"p5m2_74",question:"The company's international presence has _____ from 5 countries to 22 in just four years.",options:["A) grown","B) expanded","C) increased","D) all of the above"],answer:"D",explanation:"All three options are correct because 'grown,' 'expanded,' and 'increased' all describe a measurable rise in the number of countries in which the company operates, all collocating naturally with 'from X to Y' in business reporting. 'Grown' is correct because it is a natural intransitive verb for describing development or enlargement, here moving from 5 to 22 countries. 'Expanded' is correct because it means widened or extended in scope, appropriate for describing geographic growth of an international presence. 'Increased' is correct because it describes a rise in number or quantity, natural when a specific range ('from 5 to 22') is given.",category:"Vocabulary"},
  {id:"p5m2_75",question:"The team will _____ a feasibility study before any investment is approved.",options:["A) conduct","B) carry out","C) undertake","D) all of the above"],answer:"D",explanation:"All three options are correct because 'conduct,' 'carry out,' and 'undertake' are all standard collocations with 'a feasibility study' in professional and academic English. 'Conduct' is correct because it is the most formal and common verb for performing a structured analytical process such as a study or survey. 'Carry out' is correct because it is a phrasal verb meaning to perform or execute a task, natural and widely used in operational and project management contexts. 'Undertake' is correct because it means to commit to and begin performing a task, appropriate when emphasizing the team's responsibility to complete the feasibility study.",category:"Vocabulary"},
  {id:"p5m2_76",question:"The company's strong earnings _____ the market's expectations for the quarter.",options:["A) beat","B) exceeded","C) surpassed","D) all of the above"],answer:"D",explanation:"All three options are correct because 'beat,' 'exceeded,' and 'surpassed' all describe the earnings performing better than what the market had anticipated, all standard collocations with 'expectations' in financial reporting. 'Beat' is correct because it is the most colloquial and widely used term in financial journalism for performing better than a forecast or estimate. 'Exceeded' is correct because it means went beyond a limit or expectation, the most formal and neutral option, common in corporate announcements. 'Surpassed' is correct because it means went beyond in quality or amount, a near-synonym of 'exceeded' with a slightly more emphatic tone.",category:"Vocabulary"},
  {id:"p5m2_77",question:"The management team _____ the acquisition will be completed by Q2.",options:["A) expects","B) anticipates","C) projects","D) all of the above"],answer:"D",explanation:"All three options are correct because 'expects,' 'anticipates,' and 'projects' are all standard forecasting verbs that introduce a that-clause about a future event, all widely used in business communication and financial reporting. 'Expects' is correct because it is the most general and common term for believing something will happen, natural in both formal and informal business contexts. 'Anticipates' is correct because it means looks forward to or foresees something, with a slightly more forward-planning connotation than 'expects.' 'Projects' is correct because it means formally estimates or forecasts based on data, particularly used in financial and business planning contexts.",category:"Vocabulary"},
  {id:"p5m2_78",question:"The client _____ a preference for in-person meetings over video calls.",options:["A) expressed","B) stated","C) indicated","D) all of the above"],answer:"D",explanation:"All three options are correct because 'expressed,' 'stated,' and 'indicated' all describe the client communicating a preference, each with a slightly different implication about the directness or formality of the communication. 'Expressed a preference' is correct because it is the most idiomatic collocation for communicating a preference, widely used in customer service and business English. 'Stated a preference' is correct because it means clearly declared or set out a preference, implying a direct and explicit communication. 'Indicated a preference' is correct because it means showed or signaled a preference, which can be either direct or indirect, making it the most flexible of the three options.",category:"Vocabulary"},
  {id:"p5m2_79",question:"The new payment gateway has _____ the time taken to process transactions.",options:["A) reduced","B) shortened","C) cut","D) all of the above"],answer:"D",explanation:"All three options are correct because 'reduced,' 'shortened,' and 'cut' all describe a decrease in the duration of transaction processing, and all are natural collocations with 'time' in technology and business contexts. 'Reduced' is correct because it is the most general verb for making something smaller or less, widely used in both formal and informal business reporting. 'Shortened' is correct because it specifically implies making a duration briefer, the most precisely matched synonym for reducing time. 'Cut' is correct because it is an emphatic, direct verb for reducing something significantly, common in business English when describing efficiency improvements.",category:"Vocabulary"},
  {id:"p5m2_80",question:"The company _____ its workforce by 8% as part of the restructuring plan.",options:["A) reduced","B) downsized","C) cut","D) all of the above"],answer:"D",explanation:"All three options are correct because 'reduced,' 'downsized,' and 'cut' are all standard verbs for describing a decrease in the number of employees as part of a restructuring plan. 'Reduced' is correct because it is the most neutral and general term for making the workforce smaller, appropriate in formal corporate and news contexts. 'Downsized' is correct because it is a business-specific term meaning to reduce the size of a company's workforce, often used as a euphemism for layoffs in corporate restructuring contexts. 'Cut' is correct because it is a direct and emphatic verb describing a reduction, widely used in business journalism and company announcements about workforce reductions.",category:"Vocabulary"},
  {id:"p5m2_81",question:"The initiative _____ to align the company's operations with its sustainability goals.",options:["A) seeks","B) aims","C) is designed","D) all of the above"],answer:"D",explanation:"All three options are correct because 'seeks,' 'aims,' and 'is designed' all introduce an infinitive ('to align') to describe the purpose or objective of the initiative, all standard in business and sustainability reporting. 'Seeks to align' is correct because it means tries or strives to achieve alignment, a common formal construction for describing the purpose of corporate programs. 'Aims to align' is correct because it means has as its objective, the most widely used expression of a stated goal or intention in business English. 'Is designed to align' is correct because it means was created or structured with the specific purpose of achieving alignment, emphasizing intentional planning.",category:"Vocabulary"},
  {id:"p5m2_82",question:"The company's strong performance _____ the confidence of its long-term investors.",options:["A) reinforced","B) bolstered","C) strengthened","D) all of the above"],answer:"D",explanation:"All three options are correct because 'reinforced,' 'bolstered,' and 'strengthened' all describe a positive effect on investor confidence resulting from strong performance, each carrying a similar but slightly different nuance. 'Reinforced' is correct because it means made stronger or confirmed, often implying that existing confidence was supported by new evidence. 'Bolstered' is correct because it means propped up or gave additional support to, often implying that confidence needed or received active support from the performance data. 'Strengthened' is correct because it means made stronger, the most direct and general synonym of the three, widely used in financial and business reporting.",category:"Vocabulary"},
  {id:"p5m2_83",question:"The budget _____ an increase in spending on employee training and development.",options:["A) includes","B) incorporates","C) allocates for","D) both A and B"],answer:"D",explanation:"'Includes' and 'incorporates' are both correct because both describe the budget containing or integrating an increase in training spending as one of its components, while 'allocates for' introduces a structural mismatch. 'Includes' is correct because it means contains as part of a whole, the most natural and common verb for listing what a budget covers. 'Incorporates' is correct because it means integrates or embeds something as a component, a slightly more formal synonym that works equally well in this sentence. 'Allocates for' is wrong in this structure because 'allocates for an increase' is an unnatural collocation; the correct form would be 'allocates funds for training,' making it structurally incompatible with the sentence as written.",category:"Vocabulary"},
  {id:"p5m2_84",question:"The expansion into the Asian market has _____ better than expected.",options:["A) gone","B) progressed","C) performed","D) all of the above"],answer:"D",explanation:"All three options are correct because 'gone,' 'progressed,' and 'performed' can all follow 'has' as part of a present perfect construction and naturally collocate with 'better than expected' to describe the expansion's outcome. 'Gone better than expected' is correct because 'go' in the sense of 'proceed' is a very common idiomatic expression for describing how an activity or initiative has turned out. 'Progressed better than expected' is correct because it means advanced or developed more positively than anticipated, appropriate for describing the trajectory of a market entry. 'Performed better than expected' is correct because it means yielded results superior to projections, a standard expression in business performance reviews.",category:"Vocabulary"},
  {id:"p5m2_85",question:"The team _____ a presentation on the market entry strategy for the board.",options:["A) gave","B) delivered","C) made","D) all of the above"],answer:"D",explanation:"All three options are correct because 'gave,' 'delivered,' and 'made' are all standard collocations with 'a presentation' in English, each describing the act of presenting to the board. 'Gave a presentation' is correct because 'give a presentation' is one of the most common and natural collocations in business English for delivering formal content to an audience. 'Delivered a presentation' is correct because it means presented formally and competently, with a slightly more professional or accomplished connotation than 'gave.' 'Made a presentation' is correct because 'make a presentation' is equally idiomatic and widely used, especially in North American business English.",category:"Vocabulary"},
  {id:"p5m2_86",question:"The company's profitability _____ significantly once the new pricing model was adopted.",options:["A) improved","B) increased","C) rose","D) all of the above"],answer:"D",explanation:"All three options are correct because 'improved,' 'increased,' and 'rose' all describe an upward change in the company's profitability following adoption of the new model, all grammatically valid intransitive verbs in this context. 'Improved' is correct because it means got better, appropriate when profitability moved from a lower to a higher quality or level. 'Increased' is correct because it means grew in amount or degree, the most direct and neutral term for describing a quantitative rise in profitability. 'Rose' is correct because it is the past tense of 'rise,' meaning went up, commonly used in financial reporting to describe upward movement in metrics.",category:"Vocabulary"},
  {id:"p5m2_87",question:"The Director of Finance _____ a comprehensive review of all operating costs.",options:["A) ordered","B) commissioned","C) requested","D) all of the above"],answer:"D",explanation:"All three options are correct because 'ordered,' 'commissioned,' and 'requested' all describe the Director of Finance initiating the review, each with a slightly different implication about authority or formality. 'Ordered' is correct because it implies using hierarchical authority to direct someone to perform the review, appropriate for a director giving instructions. 'Commissioned' is correct because it means formally instructed or authorized someone to perform a specific task, often implying an external party or a significant undertaking. 'Requested' is correct because it means asked for the review, the most neutral and least authoritative of the three, appropriate in contexts where the Director works collaboratively.",category:"Vocabulary"},
  {id:"p5m2_88",question:"Having _____ the proposal, the committee moved to discuss the implementation timeline.",options:["A) reviewed","B) approved","C) endorsed","D) all of the above"],answer:"D",explanation:"All three options are correct because 'reviewed,' 'approved,' and 'endorsed' can all follow 'having' to form a perfect participle clause describing an action the committee completed before moving to the next agenda item. 'Having reviewed the proposal' is correct because it means after the committee examined or read through the proposal, the most neutral action that would naturally precede a discussion. 'Having approved the proposal' is correct because it means after formally accepting it, implying the discussion of the timeline follows the approval decision. 'Having endorsed the proposal' is correct because it means after formally expressing support for it, equally valid as a prior action that allows the committee to move forward.",category:"Grammar"},
  {id:"p5m2_89",question:"The _____ of the new regional office has been delayed due to permit issues.",options:["A) opening","B) launch","C) inauguration","D) all of the above"],answer:"D",explanation:"All three options are correct because 'opening,' 'launch,' and 'inauguration' are all nouns that describe the event of a new office beginning operations, all appropriate in the context of a delayed commencement. 'Opening' is correct because it is the most general and widely used noun for the start of a new venue or facility, natural in both informal and formal contexts. 'Launch' is correct because it describes the formal introduction of a new location or operation to the public or business community, common in corporate communications. 'Inauguration' is correct because it refers to a formal ceremony marking the beginning of operations, appropriate for a notable new regional office.",category:"Vocabulary"},
  {id:"p5m2_90",question:"The organization has _____ a series of workshops to build digital literacy across all departments.",options:["A) organized","B) run","C) hosted","D) all of the above"],answer:"D",explanation:"All three options are correct because 'organized,' 'run,' and 'hosted' are all standard verbs describing the act of arranging and conducting workshops, each capturing a slightly different aspect of the role taken. 'Organized' is correct because it means planned and arranged the series of workshops, emphasizing the preparatory and logistical work. 'Run' is correct because it means managed and conducted the workshops, emphasizing the execution of the events. 'Hosted' is correct because it means provided the venue and managed the series as host, emphasizing the organizational role of the institution rather than just the logistics.",category:"Vocabulary"},
  {id:"p5m2_91",question:"The new policy is _____ to take effect at the start of the next fiscal year.",options:["A) scheduled","B) set","C) due","D) all of the above"],answer:"D",explanation:"All three options are correct because 'scheduled to,' 'set to,' and 'due to' are all standard passive or adjectival constructions followed by an infinitive that express a planned future event or obligation. 'Scheduled to take effect' is correct because it means officially planned for a specific time, implying a formal timetable has been established. 'Set to take effect' is correct because it means arranged or prepared to happen at a particular time, a common expression in business and news English. 'Due to take effect' is correct because it means expected or obligated to happen at a specific time, often used when discussing policy or regulatory timelines.",category:"Vocabulary"},
  {id:"p5m2_92",question:"The company has _____ to invest $2 billion in clean energy over the next decade.",options:["A) pledged","B) committed","C) promised","D) all of the above"],answer:"D",explanation:"All three options are correct because 'pledged,' 'committed,' and 'promised' all describe making a formal declaration of intention to invest, each conveying a binding or serious commitment. 'Pledged' is correct because it means made a solemn promise or public declaration, commonly used for formal financial or sustainability commitments. 'Committed' is correct because it means formally dedicated resources or made a binding obligation, widely used in corporate announcements and ESG contexts. 'Promised' is correct because it means gave an assurance of a future action, the most general of the three and appropriate in both formal and informal reporting of investment intentions.",category:"Vocabulary"},
  {id:"p5m2_93",question:"The new regulation _____ all companies to report greenhouse gas emissions annually.",options:["A) requires","B) compels","C) mandates","D) all of the above"],answer:"D",explanation:"All three options are correct because 'requires,' 'compels,' and 'mandates' all mean to legally or officially obligate companies to take an action, and all are followed by an object plus an infinitive ('requires companies to report'). 'Requires' is correct because it is the most common and neutral term for creating a legal or regulatory obligation, widely used in rule-making language. 'Compels' is correct because it means forces or strongly obliges, often implying that non-compliance has consequences, appropriate in a regulatory context. 'Mandates' is correct because it is a formal legal term meaning officially orders or requires, commonly used in governmental and regulatory language.",category:"Vocabulary"},
  {id:"p5m2_94",question:"The firm _____ to complete the merger without any disruption to ongoing services.",options:["A) intends","B) plans","C) aims","D) all of the above"],answer:"D",explanation:"All three options are correct because 'intends,' 'plans,' and 'aims' are all standard verbs expressing a future intention or goal, all followed by an infinitive ('to complete'), and all appropriate in business announcements about merger timelines. 'Intends to complete' is correct because it means has the firm purpose or resolve to achieve something, commonly used when companies make formal statements about their objectives. 'Plans to complete' is correct because it means has made arrangements to achieve something, slightly more concrete than 'intends' as it implies preparations are in place. 'Aims to complete' is correct because it means has as a target or objective, emphasizing aspiration and direction.",category:"Vocabulary"},
  {id:"p5m2_95",question:"The CEO _____ the importance of the firm's long-term sustainability strategy.",options:["A) highlighted","B) stressed","C) underscored","D) all of the above"],answer:"D",explanation:"All three options are correct because 'highlighted,' 'stressed,' and 'underscored' are all synonymous verbs meaning to draw attention to or emphasize something's significance, all natural in the context of a CEO communicating a strategic priority. 'Highlighted' is correct because it means drew special attention to, often implying making something stand out from other topics discussed. 'Stressed' is correct because it means gave particular emphasis to, implying special weight was placed on the importance of sustainability. 'Underscored' is correct because it means reinforced or emphasized, a formal synonym that adds gravity to the CEO's statement, common in business journalism.",category:"Vocabulary"},
  {id:"p5m2_96",question:"The finance team _____ cost savings of over $3 million from the new procurement model.",options:["A) achieved","B) realized","C) delivered","D) all of the above"],answer:"D",explanation:"All three options are correct because 'achieved,' 'realized,' and 'delivered' all describe the finance team successfully generating cost savings as a concrete outcome, all standard collocations in financial and operational reporting. 'Achieved' is correct because it means successfully brought about a result after effort, the most general and widely used term for reaching a financial target. 'Realized' is correct because it is a financial term meaning converted potential savings into actual results, particularly appropriate in the context of procurement efficiency. 'Delivered' is correct because it means produced or yielded a concrete result, emphasizing that the savings were actually achieved and not just projected.",category:"Vocabulary"},
  {id:"p5m2_97",question:"The report _____ the performance of each region during the previous fiscal year.",options:["A) summarizes","B) reviews","C) analyzes","D) all of the above"],answer:"D",explanation:"All three options are correct because 'summarizes,' 'reviews,' and 'analyzes' all describe what the report does with the regional performance data, each emphasizing a different function. 'Summarizes' is correct because it means gives a concise overview of the key points, appropriate when a report condenses data into a readable format. 'Reviews' is correct because it means examines or assesses the performance in a structured way, the most general term for what an annual or fiscal year report does. 'Analyzes' is correct because it means examines in detail to understand underlying patterns and causes, appropriate for a report that goes beyond description to provide insight.",category:"Vocabulary"},
  {id:"p5m2_98",question:"The HR department has _____ a new performance appraisal framework.",options:["A) introduced","B) rolled out","C) launched","D) all of the above"],answer:"D",explanation:"All three options are correct because 'introduced,' 'rolled out,' and 'launched' all describe the HR department bringing a new framework into use, each with a slightly different emphasis on the process. 'Introduced' is correct because it means presented or brought into use for the first time, the most general term for establishing a new system or framework. 'Rolled out' is correct because it is a phrasal verb meaning to deploy something in stages or across an organization, appropriate for a framework being implemented across departments. 'Launched' is correct because it means formally started or released to the organization, implying a notable or structured introduction of the new appraisal system.",category:"Vocabulary"},
  {id:"p5m2_99",question:"The firm's market capitalization _____ $10 billion for the first time last quarter.",options:["A) exceeded","B) surpassed","C) topped","D) all of the above"],answer:"D",explanation:"All three options are correct because 'exceeded,' 'surpassed,' and 'topped' all describe the market capitalization going beyond a specific threshold ($10 billion) for the first time, all standard in financial reporting. 'Exceeded' is correct because it means went beyond a specified amount, the most formal and precise term for surpassing a numerical milestone. 'Surpassed' is correct because it means went beyond or outstripped, a near-synonym of 'exceeded' with a slightly more emphatic tone. 'Topped' is correct because it means reached above or surpassed a figure, a more colloquial expression widely used in financial journalism to describe crossing a key threshold.",category:"Vocabulary"},
  {id:"p5m2_100",question:"The company _____ a policy of promoting from within wherever possible.",options:["A) follows","B) maintains","C) practices","D) all of the above"],answer:"D",explanation:"All three options are correct because 'follows,' 'maintains,' and 'practices' all describe a company consistently adhering to a stated policy, each with a slightly different nuance. 'Follows a policy' is correct because it means complies with or acts in accordance with a stated rule or guideline, the most common collocation. 'Maintains a policy' is correct because it means keeps the policy in place over time, emphasizing continuity and commitment. 'Practices a policy' is correct because it means puts the policy into consistent action, emphasizing that the principle is actively implemented rather than merely declared.",category:"Vocabulary"},
  {id:"p5m2_101",question:"She was _____ to join the executive team as Chief Operating Officer.",options:["A) promoted","B) appointed","C) elevated","D) all of the above"],answer:"D",explanation:"All three options are correct because 'promoted,' 'appointed,' and 'elevated' all describe her being placed into the COO role, each with a slightly different implication about the nature of the movement. 'Promoted' is correct because it means advanced to a higher role, implying an internal move to a more senior position within the same organization. 'Appointed' is correct because it means officially selected or designated for a position, appropriate for both internal and external hires to executive roles. 'Elevated' is correct because it means raised to a higher rank or status, a formal term often used to emphasize the significance of the promotion to executive level.",category:"Vocabulary"},
  {id:"p5m2_102",question:"The technology _____ processes that previously required manual input.",options:["A) automates","B) streamlines","C) optimizes","D) all of the above"],answer:"D",explanation:"All three options are correct because 'automates,' 'streamlines,' and 'optimizes' all describe the positive effect of the technology on previously manual processes, each emphasizing a different aspect of improvement. 'Automates' is correct because it means converts processes to run automatically without manual input, directly addressing the 'previously required manual input' aspect of the sentence. 'Streamlines' is correct because it means makes processes more efficient and less complicated, appropriate for describing operational improvements driven by technology. 'Optimizes' is correct because it means adjusts processes to achieve the best possible performance, encompassing a broader improvement beyond just eliminating manual steps.",category:"Vocabulary"},
  {id:"p5m2_103",question:"The company has _____ a dedicated team to handle social media and digital communications.",options:["A) established","B) set up","C) created","D) all of the above"],answer:"D",explanation:"All three options are correct because 'established,' 'set up,' and 'created' all describe the act of forming a new team within the organization, each at a slightly different register. 'Established' is correct because it is the most formal option, meaning formally founded or put in place with official status, appropriate for a company announcement. 'Set up' is correct because it is a phrasal verb meaning to put in place and organize, widely used in business contexts for forming teams or structures. 'Created' is correct because it means brought into existence, the most general term, natural when referring to the formation of a new functional group.",category:"Vocabulary"},
  {id:"p5m2_104",question:"The compliance team _____ a review of all third-party vendor contracts.",options:["A) initiated","B) began","C) launched","D) all of the above"],answer:"D",explanation:"All three options are correct because 'initiated,' 'began,' and 'launched' all describe the compliance team starting the review process, each with a slightly different connotation of formality or intent. 'Initiated' is correct because it means formally started or set in motion, often implying a deliberate and official beginning of a process. 'Began' is correct because it is the most neutral and general past tense of 'begin,' accurately describing the start of the review. 'Launched' is correct because it means started with purpose or officially introduced, implying the review was announced and begun as a notable undertaking.",category:"Vocabulary"},
  {id:"p5m2_105",question:"The CFO _____ a conservative approach to capital allocation during the downturn.",options:["A) adopted","B) took","C) pursued","D) all of the above"],answer:"D",explanation:"All three options are correct because 'adopted,' 'took,' and 'pursued' are all standard collocations with 'approach' in business English, each describing the CFO choosing and implementing a strategy. 'Adopted' is correct because it means formally took on or accepted a particular approach as the guiding strategy, implying a deliberate choice. 'Took' is correct because 'take an approach' is a very common and idiomatic collocation meaning to choose to act in a particular way. 'Pursued' is correct because it means actively followed or continued with an approach over time, emphasizing the ongoing nature of the conservative strategy during the downturn.",category:"Vocabulary"},
  {id:"p5m2_106",question:"The company _____ a robust internal audit program to ensure compliance.",options:["A) maintains","B) operates","C) runs","D) all of the above"],answer:"D",explanation:"All three options are correct because 'maintains,' 'operates,' and 'runs' all describe the company keeping a functioning internal audit program in place, all natural collocations in governance and compliance language. 'Maintains' is correct because it means keeps something in good working order over time, emphasizing the ongoing commitment to sustaining the audit program. 'Operates' is correct because it means runs or manages a system or process, appropriate for describing the active functioning of an audit program. 'Runs' is correct because it is the most informal of the three but equally valid, commonly used in business English to describe managing or conducting a program or process.",category:"Vocabulary"},
  {id:"p5m2_107",question:"The new hires will _____ a two-week induction program before joining their teams.",options:["A) undergo","B) complete","C) attend","D) all of the above"],answer:"D",explanation:"All three options are correct because 'undergo,' 'complete,' and 'attend' all describe the new hires' participation in the induction program, each highlighting a slightly different aspect of their involvement. 'Undergo' is correct because it means experience or go through a process, often used for programs that involve a sequence of required activities such as onboarding or training. 'Complete' is correct because it means finish all required elements of, emphasizing that the new hires must go through every part of the program. 'Attend' is correct because it means be present at, appropriate when the program consists of sessions, workshops, or classes that require physical or virtual presence.",category:"Vocabulary"},
  {id:"p5m2_108",question:"The board _____ the company's performance against the benchmarks set at the start of the year.",options:["A) measured","B) assessed","C) evaluated","D) all of the above"],answer:"D",explanation:"All three options are correct because 'measured,' 'assessed,' and 'evaluated' all describe the board examining the company's performance in relation to established benchmarks, each with a slightly different methodological emphasis. 'Measured' is correct because it means quantified or compared performance against a standard, implying a data-driven comparison with the benchmarks. 'Assessed' is correct because it means judged or estimated the performance after consideration of evidence, appropriate for a board-level strategic review. 'Evaluated' is correct because it means systematically analyzed and judged the quality or value of the performance, the most comprehensive of the three.",category:"Vocabulary"},
  {id:"p5m2_109",question:"The firm has _____ new quality standards that exceed current industry requirements.",options:["A) set","B) established","C) introduced","D) all of the above"],answer:"D",explanation:"All three options are correct because 'set,' 'established,' and 'introduced' all describe the firm creating and implementing new quality standards that go beyond existing industry norms. 'Set' is correct because 'set standards' is the most idiomatic and common collocation, meaning to define and put in place a benchmark or criterion. 'Established' is correct because it means formally created and put in place with official status, appropriate for standards that are to be applied systematically. 'Introduced' is correct because it means brought into use for the first time, natural when the standards are newly created and represent a change from previous practice.",category:"Vocabulary"},
  {id:"p5m2_110",question:"The marketing team _____ the key findings from the customer satisfaction survey.",options:["A) presented","B) shared","C) reported","D) all of the above"],answer:"D",explanation:"All three options are correct because 'presented,' 'shared,' and 'reported' all describe the marketing team communicating survey findings to an audience, each with a slightly different implication about format and formality. 'Presented' is correct because it means displayed or communicated information formally to an audience, often in a structured format such as slides or a meeting. 'Shared' is correct because it means made available to others, implying distribution of the findings, which could be formal or informal. 'Reported' is correct because it means formally communicated findings, often in writing or at a meeting, the most neutral and widely used term in a corporate research context.",category:"Vocabulary"},
  {id:"p5m2_111",question:"The government _____ additional incentives to attract foreign direct investment.",options:["A) introduced","B) offered","C) announced","D) all of the above"],answer:"D",explanation:"All three options are correct because 'introduced,' 'offered,' and 'announced' all describe the government making additional incentives available to attract investment, each with a slightly different emphasis on the action taken. 'Introduced' is correct because it means brought new incentives into existence or into the policy framework, emphasizing the creation of new measures. 'Offered' is correct because it means made available or presented as an option, emphasizing that the incentives are being provided for foreign investors to take up. 'Announced' is correct because it means publicly declared the existence of, emphasizing the communication of the incentives to potential investors.",category:"Vocabulary"},
  {id:"p5m2_112",question:"The CEO _____ a bold vision for the company's next decade of growth.",options:["A) articulated","B) outlined","C) presented","D) all of the above"],answer:"D",explanation:"All three options are correct because 'articulated,' 'outlined,' and 'presented' all describe the CEO communicating a strategic vision, each emphasizing a slightly different aspect of the communication. 'Articulated' is correct because it means expressed clearly and effectively, often implying the vision was communicated in a sophisticated and persuasive manner. 'Outlined' is correct because it means described the main features or structure of the vision, appropriate when the CEO gave an overview of the key elements without full detail. 'Presented' is correct because it means formally introduced or communicated to an audience, the most neutral and general of the three options.",category:"Vocabulary"},
  {id:"p5m2_113",question:"The company _____ its environmental impact by 30% in the last two years.",options:["A) reduced","B) cut","C) lowered","D) all of the above"],answer:"D",explanation:"All three options are correct because 'reduced,' 'cut,' and 'lowered' all describe a decrease in environmental impact, all collocating naturally with a percentage figure in sustainability reporting. 'Reduced' is correct because it is the most standard and formal verb for describing a decrease in environmental metrics, widely used in ESG and sustainability reports. 'Cut' is correct because it is an emphatic and direct verb for reducing something significantly, common in environmental communications to signal strong action. 'Lowered' is correct because it means decreased or brought down, a natural synonym that collocates well with impact metrics in environmental reporting.",category:"Vocabulary"},
  {id:"p5m2_114",question:"The strategic plan was _____ after extensive consultation with all stakeholders.",options:["A) developed","B) formulated","C) created","D) all of the above"],answer:"D",explanation:"All three options are correct because 'developed,' 'formulated,' and 'created' all describe the strategic plan being produced as a result of stakeholder consultation, each with a slightly different emphasis on the process. 'Developed' is correct because it means built up or elaborated over time, appropriate for a strategic plan that emerged from an extensive process of consultation. 'Formulated' is correct because it means carefully devised or expressed in a systematic way, emphasizing the deliberate and structured nature of the planning process. 'Created' is correct because it means brought into existence, the most general of the three, natural when emphasizing that the plan is a new document resulting from the consultation.",category:"Vocabulary"},
  {id:"p5m2_115",question:"The company _____ its partnership with the university to fund research initiatives.",options:["A) extended","B) renewed","C) continued","D) all of the above"],answer:"D",explanation:"All three options are correct because 'extended,' 'renewed,' and 'continued' all describe the company maintaining or prolonging its partnership with the university, each with a slightly different implication about the nature of the ongoing relationship. 'Extended' is correct because it means prolonged the partnership beyond its original end date or scope, implying an expansion of the existing agreement. 'Renewed' is correct because it means formally revived or re-established the partnership for a new term, appropriate when a previous agreement came up for review. 'Continued' is correct because it means carried on with an existing arrangement without interruption, the most neutral description of ongoing partnership.",category:"Vocabulary"},
  {id:"p5m2_116",question:"The team _____ a breakthrough after months of intensive research.",options:["A) achieved","B) made","C) reached","D) both A and B"],answer:"D",explanation:"'Achieved' and 'made' are both correct because 'achieve a breakthrough' and 'make a breakthrough' are both well-established idiomatic collocations in English meaning to reach a significant discovery or advance. 'Achieved a breakthrough' is correct because 'achieve' collocates naturally with 'breakthrough' to describe successfully reaching an important goal after sustained effort. 'Made a breakthrough' is correct because 'make a breakthrough' is arguably the most common and idiomatic collocation in English for this concept, widely used in academic and business contexts. 'Reached a breakthrough' is wrong because 'reach' does not form a standard collocation with 'breakthrough'; the correct collocations for 'reach' are 'reach an agreement,' 'reach a decision,' or 'reach a conclusion.'",category:"Vocabulary"},
  {id:"p5m2_117",question:"The company has _____ its operations to include new product categories.",options:["A) diversified","B) expanded","C) extended","D) all of the above"],answer:"D",explanation:"All three options are correct because 'diversified,' 'expanded,' and 'extended' all describe the company broadening its operations to cover new product categories, each with a slightly different strategic nuance. 'Diversified' is correct because it means broadened the range of activities or products to reduce reliance on a single area, a key strategic term in business and investment. 'Expanded' is correct because it means increased in scope or scale, appropriate for a company growing its operational footprint to include new categories. 'Extended' is correct because it means stretched or widened to cover something new, natural when describing the addition of new product categories to an existing operational structure.",category:"Vocabulary"},
  {id:"p5m2_118",question:"The CEO _____ her team for their outstanding work on the product launch.",options:["A) praised","B) thanked","C) commended","D) all of the above"],answer:"D",explanation:"All three options are correct because 'praised,' 'thanked,' and 'commended' all describe the CEO expressing appreciation or recognition to the team, each with a slightly different focus. 'Praised' is correct because it means expressed strong approval of, focusing on the quality of the team's work as outstanding. 'Thanked' is correct because it means expressed gratitude to, emphasizing the CEO's appreciation for the team's contribution to the product launch. 'Commended' is correct because it means formally praised or recommended, carrying an official or elevated tone appropriate for a CEO publicly recognizing a team's achievement.",category:"Vocabulary"},
  {id:"p5m2_119",question:"The board _____ a new long-term incentive plan for senior executives.",options:["A) approved","B) adopted","C) introduced","D) all of the above"],answer:"D",explanation:"All three options are correct because 'approved,' 'adopted,' and 'introduced' all describe the board giving effect to a new long-term incentive plan, each emphasizing a different aspect of the decision. 'Approved' is correct because it means formally accepted or gave sanction to the plan after review, the most common board-level action for a new compensation plan. 'Adopted' is correct because it means formally accepted and put into use, implying the plan was accepted as official policy of the organization. 'Introduced' is correct because it means brought in or presented for the first time, appropriate when highlighting that this is a new plan being put in place.",category:"Vocabulary"},
  {id:"p5m2_120",question:"The company has _____ its digital infrastructure to support the growing workforce.",options:["A) upgraded","B) strengthened","C) modernized","D) all of the above"],answer:"D",explanation:"All three options are correct because 'upgraded,' 'strengthened,' and 'modernized' all describe improvements made to the digital infrastructure to meet the needs of a growing workforce, each with a slightly different focus. 'Upgraded' is correct because it means improved to a newer or more advanced version or level, appropriate for describing enhancements to technology systems. 'Strengthened' is correct because it means made more robust or capable, emphasizing that the infrastructure is now better able to handle increased demand. 'Modernized' is correct because it means brought up to date with current standards or technologies, appropriate when the improvements involve replacing outdated systems.",category:"Vocabulary"},
  {id:"p5m2_121",question:"She was _____ responsible for leading the company's global expansion strategy.",options:["A) primarily","B) chiefly","C) mainly","D) all of the above"],answer:"D",explanation:"All three options are correct because 'primarily,' 'chiefly,' and 'mainly' are all adverbs of degree meaning 'above all' or 'most importantly,' all of which naturally modify the adjective 'responsible' to indicate her foremost role. 'Primarily' is correct because it means above all else or as the most important factor, appropriate in formal business and HR contexts to describe the leading responsibility. 'Chiefly' is correct because it means mainly or especially, a slightly more formal synonym used in both written reports and corporate announcements. 'Mainly' is correct because it is the most common and conversational of the three, equally valid when indicating that global expansion was her principal duty.",category:"Word Form"},
  {id:"p5m2_122",question:"The Q3 results were _____ disappointing given the high expectations set earlier.",options:["A) broadly","B) somewhat","C) generally","D) all of the above"],answer:"D",explanation:"All three options are correct because 'broadly,' 'somewhat,' and 'generally' are all degree adverbs that can modify 'disappointing' to indicate that the results fell short of expectations to a certain extent, each carrying a slightly different nuance. 'Broadly disappointing' is correct because it means disappointing across most or all areas, used to indicate that the shortfall was widespread. 'Somewhat disappointing' is correct because it means moderately or to a limited degree disappointing, implying a softer or hedged negative assessment. 'Generally disappointing' is correct because it means disappointing in most respects, a hedging expression common in financial commentary and analyst reports.",category:"Word Form"},
  {id:"p5m2_123",question:"The launch was _____ delayed, but the product quality exceeded all expectations.",options:["A) admittedly","B) regrettably","C) unfortunately","D) all of the above"],answer:"D",explanation:"All three options are correct because 'admittedly,' 'regrettably,' and 'unfortunately' are all sentence adverbs that acknowledge the delay as a negative fact before introducing a contrasting positive ('but the product quality exceeded all expectations'). 'Admittedly' is correct because it means granted or it must be acknowledged that, signaling the speaker concedes the negative point while moving on to a positive. 'Regrettably' is correct because it means it is a matter of regret that, expressing disappointment about the delay while setting up the contrast. 'Unfortunately' is correct because it means it is unfortunate that, the most common and neutral sentence adverb for introducing an unwelcome fact.",category:"Word Form"},
  {id:"p5m2_124",question:"The team's efficiency has _____ improved since the new workflow was adopted.",options:["A) noticeably","B) markedly","C) significantly","D) all of the above"],answer:"D",explanation:"All three options are correct because 'noticeably,' 'markedly,' and 'significantly' are all adverbs indicating a meaningful and perceptible degree of improvement, all of which can modify 'improved' in this context. 'Noticeably improved' is correct because it means improved in a way that is clearly observable, implying the change is evident to those involved. 'Markedly improved' is correct because it means improved to a striking or considerable degree, often used in formal business analysis or reports. 'Significantly improved' is correct because it means improved by a meaningful or important amount, the most widely used of the three in both business and academic contexts.",category:"Word Form"},
  {id:"p5m2_125",question:"The issue was _____ resolved, with no lasting impact on client relationships.",options:["A) swiftly","B) quickly","C) promptly","D) all of the above"],answer:"D",explanation:"All three options are correct because 'swiftly,' 'quickly,' and 'promptly' are all adverbs indicating that the issue was resolved rapidly, each with a slightly different connotation of speed or professionalism. 'Swiftly resolved' is correct because it means resolved in a fast and efficient manner, a slightly more formal and emphatic choice often used in business reporting. 'Quickly resolved' is correct because it is the most general and common adverb for describing speed, appropriate in both formal and informal contexts. 'Promptly resolved' is correct because it means resolved without delay, often carrying an implication of responsiveness and professionalism, particularly in customer service or crisis management contexts.",category:"Word Form"},
  {id:"p5m2_126",question:"The company has been _____ praised for its transparent communication with stakeholders.",options:["A) widely","B) universally","C) broadly","D) all of the above"],answer:"D",explanation:"All three options are correct because 'widely,' 'universally,' and 'broadly' are all adverbs that describe the extent of the praise received, all modifying 'praised' to indicate it came from many sources or quarters. 'Widely praised' is correct because it means praised by many people or organizations across different sectors, the most common collocation in this type of statement. 'Universally praised' is correct because it means praised by all or almost all observers, the strongest of the three in implying complete or near-total consensus. 'Broadly praised' is correct because it means praised in a general or wide-ranging way, a slightly hedged alternative to 'widely' that is common in formal business and media contexts.",category:"Word Form"},
  {id:"p5m2_127",question:"The results were _____ consistent with the analyst's forecast for the year.",options:["A) broadly","B) largely","C) generally","D) all of the above"],answer:"D",explanation:"All three options are correct because 'broadly,' 'largely,' and 'generally' are all hedging adverbs that indicate the results were consistent with forecasts in most or the majority of respects, without claiming perfect alignment. 'Broadly consistent' is correct because it means consistent in general terms or across most areas, a standard hedging expression in financial and business analysis. 'Largely consistent' is correct because it means consistent in the main or for the most part, implying that any deviations were minor or limited. 'Generally consistent' is correct because it means consistent in most cases or overall, the most common hedging adverb used with 'consistent' in formal reporting.",category:"Word Form"},
  {id:"p5m2_128",question:"She _____ exceeded her sales target, achieving 145% of her annual quota.",options:["A) significantly","B) substantially","C) comfortably","D) all of the above"],answer:"D",explanation:"All three options are correct because 'significantly,' 'substantially,' and 'comfortably' all describe the degree by which she exceeded her target, each with a slightly different connotation appropriate to the context of 145% achievement. 'Significantly exceeded' is correct because it means exceeded by a meaningful and noteworthy amount, appropriate given the 45% surplus over target. 'Substantially exceeded' is correct because it means exceeded by a considerable or large amount, emphasizing the size of the outperformance. 'Comfortably exceeded' is correct because it means exceeded with a wide margin and without difficulty, a natural expression in sales performance contexts where the margin is large enough to feel effortless.",category:"Word Form"},
  {id:"p5m2_129",question:"The implementation was _____ smooth, with only minor technical issues reported.",options:["A) largely","B) mostly","C) relatively","D) all of the above"],answer:"D",explanation:"All three options are correct because 'largely,' 'mostly,' and 'relatively' are all hedging adverbs that qualify 'smooth' to acknowledge the minor technical issues while still conveying an overall positive assessment. 'Largely smooth' is correct because it means smooth in the main or for the most part, a standard hedging expression in project and implementation reporting. 'Mostly smooth' is correct because it means smooth in most respects, acknowledging that minor exceptions ('only minor technical issues') existed without undermining the overall positive characterization. 'Relatively smooth' is correct because it means smooth compared to what might have been expected or compared to similar implementations, implying a favorable assessment in context.",category:"Word Form"},
  {id:"p5m2_130",question:"The new product was _____ successful in its first market, prompting a wider rollout.",options:["A) sufficiently","B) remarkably","C) exceptionally","D) all of the above"],answer:"D",explanation:"All three options are correct because 'sufficiently,' 'remarkably,' and 'exceptionally' all modify 'successful' to describe the product's performance in its first market, each conveying a different degree of success that could logically prompt a wider rollout. 'Sufficiently successful' is correct because it means successful to the degree required, implying the results met the threshold needed to justify expansion. 'Remarkably successful' is correct because it means successful to a notable or striking degree, implying the results were impressive and therefore prompted further rollout. 'Exceptionally successful' is correct because it means successful to an unusually high degree, the strongest of the three, implying the product greatly exceeded expectations in its first market.",category:"Word Form"},
  {id:"p5m2_131",question:"The CEO's announcement came as _____ surprise to most industry analysts.",options:["A) a","B) an","C) quite a","D) both A and C"],answer:"D",explanation:"'A' and 'quite a' are both correct because 'surprise' begins with a consonant sound /s/, requiring the indefinite article 'a,' and 'quite a surprise' is an idiomatic intensified form that adds emphasis to the unexpectedness of the announcement. 'A' is correct because 'a surprise' is the standard indefinite article collocation with the countable noun 'surprise,' appropriate when noting that the announcement was unexpected. 'Quite a' is correct because 'quite a surprise' is a fixed intensifying phrase meaning a considerable or notable surprise, grammatically valid and commonly used in business and journalistic writing. 'An' is wrong because 'surprise' begins with the consonant sound /s/, so the indefinite article 'a' (not 'an') is required; 'an' is only used before vowel sounds.",category:"Grammar"},
  {id:"p5m2_132",question:"There was _____ need for alarm; the issue was quickly contained.",options:["A) no","B) little","C) not any","D) both A and B"],answer:"D",explanation:"'No' and 'little' are both correct because they each express the absence or near-absence of a need for alarm in a grammatically valid way, while 'not any' introduces a structural and stylistic problem in this context. 'No need for alarm' is correct because 'no' is the standard negative determiner used to express complete absence, creating the most direct and emphatic statement that alarm was unnecessary. 'Little need for alarm' is correct because 'little' with an uncountable or abstract noun expresses that the amount was very small or insufficient to matter, a naturally hedged equivalent. 'Not any' is wrong because while 'not any' can sometimes substitute for 'no,' the construction 'there was not any need' is awkward and unidiomatic; the standard forms are 'no need' or 'little need.'",category:"Grammar"},
  {id:"p5m2_133",question:"The merger will provide _____ significant operational benefits to both organizations.",options:["A) considerable","B) substantial","C) numerous","D) all of the above"],answer:"D",explanation:"All three options are correct because 'considerable,' 'substantial,' and 'numerous' can all precede 'significant' as an additional modifier, or replace it as the primary adjective modifying 'benefits,' with each being a standard formal business term for describing the magnitude of benefits. 'Considerable' is correct because it means large in size or extent, naturally collocating with 'benefits' to describe the scale of expected gains. 'Substantial' is correct because it means significant in size, value, or importance, a near-synonym of 'considerable' widely used in merger-related communications. 'Numerous' is correct because it means many in number, emphasizing the variety and quantity of operational benefits rather than their scale.",category:"Vocabulary"},
  {id:"p5m2_134",question:"The legal team is _____ the implications of the new data protection regulation.",options:["A) reviewing","B) assessing","C) analyzing","D) all of the above"],answer:"D",explanation:"All three options are correct because 'reviewing,' 'assessing,' and 'analyzing' all describe the legal team examining the implications of new regulation, each with a slightly different methodological emphasis. 'Reviewing' is correct because it means examining or going over the implications carefully, appropriate when the legal team reads and considers the regulatory text. 'Assessing' is correct because it means evaluating or estimating the nature and extent of the implications, implying a judgment about their significance. 'Analyzing' is correct because it means examining in detail to understand the components and effects, appropriate when the team is breaking down the regulation's impact systematically.",category:"Vocabulary"},
  {id:"p5m2_135",question:"The company has _____ a dedicated team to drive the digital transformation agenda.",options:["A) assembled","B) built","C) formed","D) all of the above"],answer:"D",explanation:"All three options are correct because 'assembled,' 'built,' and 'formed' all describe the act of bringing together individuals into a dedicated team for the digital transformation initiative. 'Assembled' is correct because it means gathered or brought together the required people into a functioning unit, implying the team was constructed from members who may have been sourced from different parts of the organization. 'Built' is correct because it means developed or put together over time, appropriate when the team was created through a deliberate process of selection and development. 'Formed' is correct because it means established or constituted as a group, the most neutral and general of the three terms.",category:"Vocabulary"},
  {id:"p5m2_136",question:"The expansion was _____ by strong demand from the Asia-Pacific region.",options:["A) driven","B) fueled","C) propelled","D) all of the above"],answer:"D",explanation:"All three options are correct because 'driven,' 'fueled,' and 'propelled' are all past participles that describe the causal role that strong demand played in the expansion, all standard in business and market analysis reporting. 'Driven' is correct because it means motivated or caused by, the most common and neutral expression for describing the force behind a business development. 'Fueled' is correct because it uses a metaphor of fuel to suggest that demand energized or sustained the expansion, common in business journalism. 'Propelled' is correct because it means pushed forward with force, implying that the demand actively accelerated or powered the expansion, a slightly more dynamic metaphor.",category:"Vocabulary"},
  {id:"p5m2_137",question:"All submissions must _____ with the specified formatting guidelines.",options:["A) comply","B) conform","C) adhere","D) both A and B"],answer:"D",explanation:"'Comply' and 'conform' are both correct because 'comply with the guidelines' and 'conform to the guidelines' are both grammatically and semantically valid expressions for meeting formatting requirements, while 'adhere' requires a different preposition. 'Comply with' is correct because it is a standard collocation meaning to act in accordance with a rule or requirement, widely used in formal and regulatory contexts. 'Conform to' is correct because it means to follow or match a specified standard, equally valid in academic and professional submission guidelines. 'Adhere' alone is wrong because the correct form is 'adhere to the guidelines,' not 'adhere with'; since the sentence ends with 'with,' choosing 'adhere' would produce the ungrammatical 'adhere with the guidelines.'",category:"Vocabulary"},
  {id:"p5m2_138",question:"The board _____ a subcommittee to review the executive compensation structure.",options:["A) established","B) formed","C) created","D) all of the above"],answer:"D",explanation:"All three options are correct because 'established,' 'formed,' and 'created' all describe the board bringing a subcommittee into existence to carry out a specific task, all standard in corporate governance language. 'Established' is correct because it means formally set up with defined authority and purpose, appropriate for a board action that has official procedural weight. 'Formed' is correct because it means constituted or organized as a group, the most neutral of the three, naturally used when describing the creation of committees or working groups. 'Created' is correct because it means brought into existence, appropriate in both formal and informal corporate contexts when a new body is being established.",category:"Vocabulary"},
  {id:"p5m2_139",question:"The company plans to _____ its customer service operations to a specialist provider.",options:["A) outsource","B) delegate","C) transfer","D) both A and C"],answer:"D",explanation:"'Outsource' and 'transfer' are both correct because both accurately describe the company moving its customer service operations to an external specialist provider, though with slightly different implications. 'Outsource' is correct because it specifically means to contract work out to an external third-party provider, directly capturing the meaning of moving operations to a specialist. 'Transfer' is correct because it means to move or relocate operations to another party, valid when the operations are being handed over to the specialist provider. 'Delegate' is wrong in this context because 'delegate' typically means to assign tasks to a subordinate within the same organization; moving operations to an external specialist provider is outsourcing or transferring, not delegating.",category:"Vocabulary"},
  {id:"p5m2_140",question:"The new platform will enable customers to _____ their accounts from any device.",options:["A) manage","B) access","C) control","D) all of the above"],answer:"D",explanation:"All three options are correct because 'manage,' 'access,' and 'control' all describe legitimate and distinct actions that customers can take with their accounts through the new platform. 'Manage' is correct because it means to administer or handle account activities such as updating information, making payments, or reviewing history. 'Access' is correct because it means to log in to or retrieve information from an account, the most fundamental action described by the sentence. 'Control' is correct because it means to have authority over and direct the settings or functions of an account, a broader term that encompasses both management and access.",category:"Vocabulary"},
  {id:"p5m2_141",question:"The sales team was _____ of their performance throughout the difficult quarter.",options:["A) proud","B) confident","C) satisfied","D) all of the above"],answer:"D",explanation:"All three options are correct because 'proud,' 'confident,' and 'satisfied' are all adjectives that follow the linking verb 'was' and are followed by 'of,' all describing positive self-assessment of the team's performance. 'Proud of their performance' is correct because it means they felt a sense of achievement and honor about what they accomplished despite the difficulty. 'Confident of their performance' is correct because it means they felt assured and certain about the quality of their results, a well-established collocation used when someone has strong belief in an outcome. 'Satisfied of their performance' is correct because in this construction 'satisfied of' means convinced or assured about the sufficiency of their efforts and results, which aligns with the formal sense of the phrase used in professional and evaluative contexts.",category:"Vocabulary"},
  {id:"p5m2_142",question:"The company _____ extensive resources to developing talent at all levels.",options:["A) devotes","B) dedicates","C) allocates","D) all of the above"],answer:"D",explanation:"All three options are correct because 'devotes,' 'dedicates,' and 'allocates' all describe the company committing resources to talent development, each with a slightly different nuance in terms of emphasis. 'Devotes resources to' is correct because it means applies or commits resources wholeheartedly to a purpose, implying strong organizational commitment. 'Dedicates resources to' is correct because it means sets apart resources specifically for a purpose, carrying a similar meaning to 'devotes' with a slightly more deliberate tone. 'Allocates resources to' is correct because it is the most technical and financial of the three, meaning to assign or distribute a specific amount of resources for a designated use.",category:"Vocabulary"},
  {id:"p5m2_143",question:"The restructuring plan _____ the consolidation of three departments into one.",options:["A) involves","B) includes","C) entails","D) all of the above"],answer:"D",explanation:"All three options are correct because 'involves,' 'includes,' and 'entails' all describe the restructuring plan encompassing the consolidation of departments as one of its elements. 'Involves' is correct because it means has as a necessary or integral part, commonly used when describing what a plan or process requires. 'Includes' is correct because it means contains as part of the whole, appropriate when the consolidation is one of several components of the restructuring plan. 'Entails' is correct because it means necessarily requires or implies, often used in formal contexts to describe the inherent demands or components of a plan.",category:"Vocabulary"},
  {id:"p5m2_144",question:"The company _____ a comprehensive due diligence process before the acquisition.",options:["A) conducted","B) undertook","C) completed","D) all of the above"],answer:"D",explanation:"All three options are correct because 'conducted,' 'undertook,' and 'completed' all describe the company carrying out or finishing the due diligence process, each with a different emphasis on the action. 'Conducted' is correct because it means performed in a systematic and professional manner, the most common verb for describing formal business processes like due diligence. 'Undertook' is correct because it means committed to and began the process, appropriate when emphasizing the decision to carry out the investigation. 'Completed' is correct because it means finished the entire process, emphasizing that the due diligence was done in full before the acquisition proceeded.",category:"Vocabulary"},
  {id:"p5m2_145",question:"The annual results _____ the success of the company's cost optimization program.",options:["A) reflect","B) demonstrate","C) highlight","D) all of the above"],answer:"D",explanation:"All three options are correct because 'reflect,' 'demonstrate,' and 'highlight' all describe what the annual results show about the cost optimization program, each with a slightly different analytical angle. 'Reflect' is correct because it means show or mirror a reality, implying that the results are an accurate representation of the program's success. 'Demonstrate' is correct because it means provide evidence of, implying that the results serve as proof of the program's effectiveness. 'Highlight' is correct because it means draw attention to or make evident, appropriate when the results make the success of the program particularly visible or notable.",category:"Vocabulary"},
  {id:"p5m2_146",question:"The senior team _____ to align on the key priorities for the next financial year.",options:["A) met","B) convened","C) gathered","D) all of the above"],answer:"D",explanation:"All three options are correct because 'met,' 'convened,' and 'gathered' all describe the senior team coming together for a meeting with the purpose of aligning on priorities. 'Met' is correct because it is the most general and common past tense verb for describing a group coming together, appropriate in both formal and informal contexts. 'Convened' is correct because it means formally assembled for a meeting, particularly used for official or structured gatherings such as board meetings or strategic sessions. 'Gathered' is correct because it means came together in one place for a common purpose, natural in the context of a group of senior leaders meeting to discuss strategic priorities.",category:"Vocabulary"},
  {id:"p5m2_147",question:"The market study _____ a significant opportunity in the premium segment.",options:["A) identified","B) uncovered","C) revealed","D) all of the above"],answer:"D",explanation:"All three options are correct because 'identified,' 'uncovered,' and 'revealed' all describe the market study finding or exposing a significant opportunity, each with a slightly different implication about how it was discovered. 'Identified' is correct because it means recognized or pinpointed through analysis, the most neutral and widely used term in market research contexts. 'Uncovered' is correct because it means discovered something that was not previously known or visible, implying the opportunity was hidden or not obvious before the study. 'Revealed' is correct because it means brought to light or disclosed, appropriate when emphasizing that the study made a previously unseen opportunity known.",category:"Vocabulary"},
  {id:"p5m2_148",question:"The team is _____ to deliver the prototype to the client by the end of the week.",options:["A) on track","B) set","C) due","D) all of the above"],answer:"D",explanation:"All three options are correct because 'on track,' 'set,' and 'due' all express that the team is expected or scheduled to deliver the prototype by the stated deadline, each with a slightly different nuance. 'On track to deliver' is correct because it means progressing as planned and expected to meet the deadline, emphasizing that progress is aligned with the schedule. 'Set to deliver' is correct because it means arranged or prepared to deliver by a specific time, a common expression in business English for planned future actions. 'Due to deliver' is correct because it means scheduled or expected to deliver at a particular time, appropriate when referring to a deadline or commitment.",category:"Vocabulary"},
  {id:"p5m2_149",question:"The initiative aims to _____ the gap between entry-level and senior compensation.",options:["A) narrow","B) close","C) bridge","D) all of the above"],answer:"D",explanation:"All three options are correct because 'narrow,' 'close,' and 'bridge' are all standard collocations with 'gap' in business and social policy English, each describing a different degree of reducing the compensation disparity. 'Narrow the gap' is correct because it means to reduce the size of the gap without necessarily eliminating it, appropriate for incremental initiatives. 'Close the gap' is correct because it means to eliminate or significantly reduce the gap, implying a stronger ambition to remove the disparity. 'Bridge the gap' is correct because it means to connect or span the two ends of the gap, often used metaphorically for initiatives that seek to make the two compensation levels more comparable.",category:"Vocabulary"},
  {id:"p5m2_150",question:"The board has _____ the new remuneration policy following shareholder consultation.",options:["A) endorsed","B) approved","C) ratified","D) all of the above"],answer:"D",explanation:"All three options are correct because 'endorsed,' 'approved,' and 'ratified' all describe the board giving formal acceptance to the new remuneration policy after consulting shareholders, each with a slightly different connotation. 'Endorsed' is correct because it means expressed formal support or approval for the policy, often implying a public declaration of backing. 'Approved' is correct because it means officially accepted the policy after review, the most general and widely used term for a board decision to accept a proposed measure. 'Ratified' is correct because it means formally confirmed or validated the policy, often used when describing a final and binding official acceptance following a prior process of consultation.",category:"Vocabulary"}
];
